if(!window.NOTES_PRELOAD)window.NOTES_PRELOAD={};window.NOTES_PRELOAD["Land Law"]={"Nature of Land": [{"id": "nature-of-land", "title": "W1: The Nature of Land", "content": "<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>THE NATURE OF LAND \u2014 COMPREHENSIVE REVISION NOTES</strong></span></h2>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>1. Structured Topic Overview</strong></span></h2>\n<p>W1 provides the conceptual foundation for all of land law. An examiner expects command of six interconnected themes:</p>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 1 \u2014 WHAT IS LAND? (THE PHYSICAL EXTENT)</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Statutory definition: s 205(1)(ix) LPA 1925 \u2014 surface; buildings/parts of buildings; corporeal hereditaments (fixtures); incorporeal hereditaments (proprietary rights with no physical substance)</li>\n<li>Maxim: cuius est solum eius est usque coelum et ad inferos \u2014 ownership extends upwards and downwards from the surface</li>\n<li>Airspace: upper (beyond ordinary use/enjoyment \u2014 Bernstein v Skyviews) vs lower (all structures that invade = trespass \u2014 Kelsen; Anchor Brewhouse)</li>\n<li>Ground below: everything beneath the surface passes with the land (Grigsby v Melville); exceptions: Crown owns gold/silver mines; Treasure Act 1996; Coal Act 1938; deep drilling >300m (Infrastructure Act 2015 s 43)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 2 \u2014 FIXTURES AND CHATTELS</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Maxim: quicquid plantatur solo, solo cedit \u2014 whatever is attached to the land becomes part of it</li>\n<li>Two-part Holland v Hodgson [1872] test: (1) degree of annexation; (2) purpose of annexation (purpose prevails \u2014 Berkley v Poulett)</li>\n<li>Purpose test: if annexed for better enjoyment of the chattel as a chattel \u2192 chattel; if to enhance the land/building \u2192 fixture</li>\n<li>Practical consequence: s 62 LPA 1925 \u2014 conveyance automatically passes all fixtures unless specifically excluded (s 62(4)); complete TA10 fixtures form to avoid disputes</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 3 \u2014 PROPRIETARY vs PERSONAL RIGHTS</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Proprietary rights: enforceable in rem (recover use/possession); binding on third parties; fixed closed list</li>\n<li>Personal rights: enforce only in personam for damages against original grantor; cannot bind third parties (e.g. licence)</li>\n<li>Nature, creation and protection all determine whether a right is proprietary or merely personal</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 4 \u2014 LEGAL ESTATES AND INTERESTS (LPA 1925)</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Two legal estates (s 1(1)): fee simple absolute in possession (freehold); term of years absolute (leasehold)</li>\n<li>Legal interests (s 1(2)): easements (correct duration); mortgages (s 1(2)(c)); rights of entry (s 1(2)(e))</li>\n<li>Equitable interests (s 1(3)): restrictive covenants; estate contracts; trust interests; easements for uncertain term</li>\n<li>Key distinction: legal interests give rights/damages as of right; equitable remedies are discretionary</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 5 \u2014 LAND CONTRACTS AND ESTATE CONTRACTS</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Formalities: s 2 LP(MP)A 1989 \u2014 in writing; all expressly agreed terms; signed by both parties</li>\n<li>Variations must also comply with s 2 (McCausland v Duncan Lawrie Ltd [1997])</li>\n<li>Proprietary effect: Walsh v Lonsdale [1882] \u2014 binding contract + specific performance available = equitable interest in land</li>\n<li>Types: contract to buy land; option; right of pre-emption; failed legal estate/interest</li>\n<li>Equitable remedies: specific performance; injunction; damages \u2014 all discretionary (clean hands: Coatsworth v Johnson)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>THEME 6 \u2014 LAND REGISTRATION: PRINCIPLES AND STRUCTURE</strong></span></h3>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\">\n<li>Key legislation: LPA 1925 (substantive rights); LRA 2002 (registration system); LP(MP)A 1989 (formalities)</li>\n<li>Three principles of registration: Mirror (register reflects all interests); Curtain (trust interests kept off title); Insurance (state indemnity for errors \u2014 Sch 8 para 1 LRA 2002)</li>\n<li>Three parts of a registered title: Property register (description, estate type, benefits); Proprietorship register (owner, restrictions, class of title); Charges register (burdens, mortgages, covenants)</li>\n<li>Transfer of freehold: 3 stages \u2014 exchange (s 2 LP(MP)A 1989); deed (s 52(1) LPA + s 1 LP(MP)A 1989); registration (s 27 LRA 2002 \u2014 title does not pass until registered)</li>\n<li>Compulsory first registration triggers (s 4 LRA): sale; mortgage; gift; assent; lease >7 yrs; assignment of unregistered lease >7 yrs to run</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>2. Summary Revision Tables</strong></span></h2>\n<h4 class=\"notes-h4\">TABLE 1 \u2014 Key Definitions & Statutory Provisions</h4>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Term</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Definition / Provision</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Source</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Land (statutory definition)</p></td>\n<td><p>\\\"The surface, buildings or parts of buildings, other corporeal hereditaments (fixtures), and incorporeal hereditaments (the benefit of proprietary rights with no physical substance)\\\"</p></td>\n<td><p>LPA 1925 s 205(1)(ix)</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Corporeal hereditament</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Tangible physical objects fixed to land (fixtures); pass with the land on sale</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>LPA 1925 s 205(1)(ix)</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Incorporeal hereditament</p></td>\n<td><p>Proprietary rights benefitting land with no physical substance; e.g. easements, covenants</p></td>\n<td><p>LPA 1925 s 205(1)(ix)</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Estate in land</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>A proprietary right of possession; determines how long the right of possession can be enjoyed</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>LPA 1925 s 1(1)</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Fee simple absolute in possession</p></td>\n<td><p>Freehold estate: highest possible estate; inheritable (\\\"fee\\\"); by any heir (\\\"simple\\\"); not determinable (\\\"absolute\\\"); current enjoyment (\\\"in possession\\\")</p></td>\n<td><p>LPA 1925 s 1(1)(a)</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Term of years absolute</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Leasehold estate: grant of possession for a certain defined duration; can be sublease of lesser duration</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>LPA 1925 s 1(1)(b)</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Freehold reversion</p></td>\n<td><p>The residue of the freehold estate after the grant of a lease; reverts to freeholder on lease expiry</p></td>\n<td><p>General law</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Commonhold</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Created out of a freehold registered estate; designed for flat owners; managed by a commonhold association (the freehold owner); alternative to long lease</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Commonhold and Leasehold Reform Act 2002</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Proprietary right</p></td>\n<td><p>Enforceable in rem; can recover use/possession of land; binding on third parties; must satisfy nature, creation and protection requirements</p></td>\n<td><p>General law</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Personal right</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Enforceable in personam for damages only; cannot bind third parties; e.g. a licence</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>General law</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Fixture</p></td>\n<td><p>Chattel annexed to land that becomes part of the land; passes automatically on sale under s 62 LPA 1925</p></td>\n<td><p>Holland v Hodgson [1872]</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Chattel</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Moveable item of personal property; does not pass with land on sale</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>General law</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Bona vacantia</p></td>\n<td><p>Land that reverts to the Crown where the freehold owner dies without heirs and without a will</p></td>\n<td><p>General law</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Estate contract</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Equitable proprietary interest arising from a binding contract to create or transfer a legal estate or interest, where specific performance is available</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Walsh v Lonsdale [1882]</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h4 class=\"notes-h4\">TABLE 2 \u2014 Proprietary vs Personal Rights</h4>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Feature</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Proprietary Right</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Personal Right</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Enforcement</p></td>\n<td><p>In rem \u2014 can recover use or possession of the land itself</p></td>\n<td><p>In personam \u2014 damages only for breach</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Third party binding?</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Yes \u2014 enforceable against new owners of burdened land (if properly protected)</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No \u2014 only against the original grantor</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Remedies</p></td>\n<td><p>Wide range including damages as of right; equitable remedies may also be available</p></td>\n<td><p>Damages only (as of right)</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Examples</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Freehold; leasehold; easement; mortgage; restrictive covenant; estate contract; trust interest</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Licence; contractual permission; purely personal agreement</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Determined by</p></td>\n<td><p>Nature of right; compliance with creation formalities; protection on the register</p></td>\n<td><p>Absence of any of the proprietary requirements</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Fixed list?</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Yes \u2014 closed list of recognised proprietary rights across statute and case law</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No \u2014 anything not on the list is personal</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h4 class=\"notes-h4\">TABLE 3 \u2014 Legal Estates and Interests: LPA 1925 s 1</h4>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Right</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule / Detail</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Statutory Basis</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>LEGAL ESTATES</p></td>\n<td><p></p></td>\n<td><p></p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Fee simple absolute in possession (freehold)</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Highest estate; inheritable by any heir; not determinable; current enjoyment; uncertain duration</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>s 1(1)(a) LPA 1925</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Term of years absolute (leasehold)</p></td>\n<td><p>Fixed or periodic certain duration; can be daily, weekly, monthly, yearly or longer; sub-leases possible</p></td>\n<td><p>s 1(1)(b) LPA 1925</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>LEGAL INTERESTS</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p></p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p></p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Easement (legal)</p></td>\n<td><p>Proprietary right to use another's land; must be granted for equivalent of freehold or leasehold duration</p></td>\n<td><p>s 1(2)(a) LPA 1925</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Mortgage (legal)</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Bundle of rights over property as security for a loan; granted by borrower over legal estate; must be created by deed + registered</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>s 1(2)(c) LPA 1925</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Right of entry</p></td>\n<td><p>Landlord's right to re-enter premises on tenant breach (forfeiture); or rentcharge owner's right to hold land if payment not made</p></td>\n<td><p>s 1(2)(e) LPA 1925</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>EQUITABLE INTERESTS (s 1(3))</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>All other interests not listed in s 1(2); recognised proprietary rights but only in equity</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>s 1(3) LPA 1925</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Restrictive covenant</p></td>\n<td><p>Promise not to do something on the burdened land; equitable interest; protects amenity of dominant land</p></td>\n<td><p>s 1(3) LPA 1925</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Estate contract</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Contractual right to a legal estate; specific performance + valid s 2 LP(MP)A 1989 document required</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Walsh v Lonsdale [1882]</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Trust interest</p></td>\n<td><p>Equitable beneficial interest; trustee holds legal title; beneficiary holds equitable interest; protected by restriction on register</p></td>\n<td><p>LPA 1925; TOLATA 1996</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Equitable easement</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Easement granted for an uncertain duration; or failed legal easement; equitable only</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>s 1(3) LPA 1925</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h4 class=\"notes-h4\">TABLE 4 \u2014 Physical Extent of Land: Airspace and Ground Below</h4>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Area</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Authority / Statute</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>General maxim</p></td>\n<td><p>Cuius est solum eius est usque coelum et ad inferos \u2014 ownership extends upward to the heavens and downward to the depths</p></td>\n<td><p>Latin maxim</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Upper airspace</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Owner has NO greater right than any member of the public; overflying aircraft does not constitute trespass; immunity from trespass for innocent aircraft flights</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Bernstein of Leigh v Skyviews [1978]; Civil Aviation Act 1982 s 76(1)</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Lower airspace</p></td>\n<td><p>That portion necessary for ordinary use and enjoyment of the land; ANY intrusion (even minor) = trespass regardless of whether damage caused</p></td>\n<td><p>Kelsen v Imperial Tobacco [1957]; Anchor Brewhouse v Berkley House [1987]; Laiqat v Majid [2005]</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Ground below \u2014 general rule</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Conveyance carries everything beneath the surface; cellar under claimant's property belongs to claimant even if accessed only from neighbour's land</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Grigsby v Melville [1974]</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Exception: minerals</p></td>\n<td><p>All mines of gold and silver belong to the Crown</p></td>\n<td><p>Prerogative rights / case law</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Exception: treasure</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Treasure (as defined) belongs to the Crown</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Treasure Act 1996</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Exception: coal</p></td>\n<td><p>Coal beneath land belongs to the Coal Authority</p></td>\n<td><p>Coal Act 1938</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Exception: deep drilling</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No trespass at depths below 300 metres; no consent of freehold owner required for deep-level drilling</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Infrastructure Act 2015 s 43</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h4 class=\"notes-h4\">TABLE 5 \u2014 Fixtures vs Chattels: Holland v Hodgson [1872] Test</h4>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Part of Test</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Cases</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>1. Degree of annexation</p></td>\n<td><p>How firmly is the object fixed to the land or building? The more firmly fixed, the more likely it is a fixture \u2014 even if fairly easy to remove, character is prima facie a fixture</p></td>\n<td><p>Holland v Hodgson [1872]</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>2. Purpose of annexation (prevails)</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Was the annexation for the more convenient use or enjoyment of the chattel as a chattel, or to enhance the building or land? Purpose overrides degree of annexation</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Berkley v Poulett [1977]</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Purpose \u2192 chattel</p></td>\n<td><p>If annexed for better enjoyment of the chattel itself as a moveable object \u2192 remains a chattel</p></td>\n<td><p>Leigh v Taylor [1902]: tapestries on battens against wall = chattel</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Purpose \u2192 fixture</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>If annexed to enhance the land or form part of the architectural design \u2192 fixture, even without firm fixing</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>D'Eyncourt v Gregory [1866]: statues incorporated into architectural design = fixtures</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Cannot be removed without destruction</p></td>\n<td><p>If a chattel cannot be removed without destruction or demolition \u2192 deemed intended to form part of the land \u2192 fixture</p></td>\n<td><p>Elitestone Ltd v Morris [1997]</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Practical consequence \u2014 s 62 LPA 1925</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Conveyance of land automatically passes all fixtures; seller may not remove after exchange of contracts; use TA10 form to agree inclusions/exclusions</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>LPA 1925 ss 62 and 62(4)</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h4 class=\"notes-h4\">TABLE 6 \u2014 Fixtures and Chattels: Cases at a Glance</h4>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Case</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Outcome</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Reason</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Holland v Hodgson [1872]</p></td>\n<td><p>Looms = fixtures; loose blocks = chattels</p></td>\n<td><p>Looms bolted to floor of mill (degree + purpose: part of mill); individual blocks merely resting on ground with no particular purpose</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Berkley v Poulett [1977]</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Statute in grounds = chattel</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Purpose: enjoyed as a chattel in its own right; purpose prevails over degree of annexation even if embedded</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>D'Eyncourt v Gregory [1866]</p></td>\n<td><p>Statues etc. = fixtures</p></td>\n<td><p>Incorporated into architectural design of building \u2014 part of architectural whole even without firm physical fixing</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Leigh v Taylor [1902]</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Tapestries = chattels</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Fixed to wall for better enjoyment as tapestries, not to enhance the building; purpose = chattel</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Elitestone Ltd v Morris [1997]</p></td>\n<td><p>Bungalow = fixture/part of land</p></td>\n<td><p>Could not be removed without demolition \u2014 deemed intended to form part of the land</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Botham v TSB Bank [1996]</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Carpets, light fittings etc. analysed</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Applied both limbs: method and degree of annexation; object and purpose of annexation \u2014 some fixtures, some chattels</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h4 class=\"notes-h4\">TABLE 7 \u2014 Transfer of a Freehold Estate: Three Stages</h4>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Stage</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Requirements</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Provisions / Effect</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>1. Exchange of contracts</p></td>\n<td><p>In writing; contains all expressly agreed terms; signed by both parties; usually deposit paid at this stage</p></td>\n<td><p>LP(MP)A 1989 s 2; parties are legally committed from this point; any variation of a material term must also comply with s 2 (McCausland v Duncan Lawrie [1997])</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>2. Completion \u2014 Deed</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Clear on face it is a deed; validly executed (individual: signed + witnessed; company: two directors / director + witness / director + secretary / company seal); delivered (by dating)</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>LPA 1925 s 52(1): legal estate must be created/transferred by deed. LP(MP)A 1989 s 1. Unregistered land: legal title passes at this stage. Registered land: title does NOT pass until registration</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>3. Registration</p></td>\n<td><p>Buyer submits completed deed (TR1) to Land Registry; Land Registry updates register</p></td>\n<td><p>LRA 2002 s 27(1): for registered land, legal title only transfers on registration. Unregistered land: must register within 2 months of completion (ss 4 and 6 LRA 2002) \u2014 failure = legal title reverts to seller</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h4 class=\"notes-h4\">TABLE 8 \u2014 Land Contracts and Estate Contracts</h4>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Issue</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule / Detail</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Formalities (s 2 LP(MP)A 1989)</p></td>\n<td><p>(1) In writing; (2) all expressly agreed terms included (can be by reference to another document); (3) signed by both parties. Cannot have oral contracts for land.</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Variations must comply with s 2</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Any variation to a material term in a land contract must comply with all three s 2 formalities; oral variation of a material term (e.g. completion date) is void (McCausland v Duncan Lawrie Ltd [1997])</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Proprietary effect (Walsh v Lonsdale)</p></td>\n<td><p>A binding land contract creates an equitable (proprietary) interest in the land \u2014 an estate contract \u2014 provided specific performance is available. \\\"Equity regards as done that which ought to be done.\\\"</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Contract to buy land</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Buyer acquires equitable interest (estate contract) between exchange and completion; seller cannot withdraw</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Option agreement</p></td>\n<td><p>Gives holder right to require seller to sell within option period; buyer not obliged to exercise; seller must sell if notice served during option period</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Right of pre-emption</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Right of first refusal if owner decides to sell; owner not obliged to sell; holder cannot force a sale</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Failed legal estate/interest</p></td>\n<td><p>If parties try to create a legal estate/interest but fail (e.g. no valid deed), equity recognises an equitable interest IF: valid s 2 LP(MP)A 1989 document + specific performance available</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Equitable remedies (discretionary)</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Specific performance (compel positive obligations); injunction (restrain breach e.g. sale to third party); damages. Must come with clean hands (Coatsworth v Johnson [1886\u201390]: tenant who breached lease terms denied equitable lease)</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h4 class=\"notes-h4\">TABLE 9 \u2014 Three Principles of Land Registration</h4>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Principle</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Qualification / Note</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Mirror principle</p></td>\n<td><p>The register should accurately reflect all interests that benefit and burden the land; purchaser should need only inspect the register</p></td>\n<td><p>Undermined by overriding interests (Sch 3 LRA 2002) \u2014 interests that bind purchasers without appearing on the register</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Curtain principle</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Trust interests (beneficial/equitable ownership) are kept off the title register; purchaser need not investigate what lies \\\"behind the curtain\\\"; simplifies conveyancing</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Achieved by restriction on proprietorship register, triggering overreaching requirement</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Insurance principle</p></td>\n<td><p>Accuracy of the register is guaranteed by the State; errors are corrected and losses are compensated by state indemnity</p></td>\n<td><p>LRA 2002 Sch 8 para 1: compensation (state indemnity) for loss caused by a mistake on the register</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h4 class=\"notes-h4\">TABLE 10 \u2014 Three Parts of a Registered Title</h4>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Register</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Contents</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Notes</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Property register</p></td>\n<td><p>Description of land by reference to title plan; type of estate (freehold/leasehold); details of any rights benefitting the land (e.g. easements)</p></td>\n<td><p>Sets out what the land IS and what rights it has</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Proprietorship register</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Name and address of registered proprietor (owner); restrictions affecting ability to deal with land; CLASS OF TITLE</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Classes: Absolute (best \u2014 only bound by registered/overriding interests); Good Leasehold; Qualified; Possessory</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Charges register</p></td>\n<td><p>Interests burdening the land; leases the land is subject to; mortgages (registered charges); restrictive covenants; equitable easements noted here</p></td>\n<td><p>Purchaser must check this register for all encumbrances</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h4 class=\"notes-h4\">TABLE 11 \u2014 Classes of Registered Title</h4>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Class</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>When Granted</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Effect / Limitation</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Absolute</p></td>\n<td><p>Best form; Land Registry satisfied title is good; most common</p></td>\n<td><p>Land only bound by interests registered on title and overriding interests; fully guaranteed title</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Good Leasehold</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Satisfied as to leaseholder's title only, not the freeholder's; occurs where freehold title is unregistered and evidence not submitted</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>May be subject to third party interests arising from defect in freehold title</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Qualified</p></td>\n<td><p>Land Registry has identified a defect in title, which is specified on the register; rare</p></td>\n<td><p>Title is subject to the specified defect; less certainty for purchaser</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Possessory</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Applicant is in possession or receiving rents/profits; no other class available; typically adverse possession (\\\"squatters' rights\\\"); title deeds lost or destroyed</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>May be bound by third party interests created before date of first registration even if not noted on title</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h4 class=\"notes-h4\">TABLE 12 \u2014 Compulsory First Registration Triggers (s 4 LRA 2002)</h4>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Triggering Event</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Notes</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Transfer of freehold estate by sale, gift or court order</p></td>\n<td><p>Most common trigger; must register within 2 months or title reverts to seller</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Grant of a new lease for a term of more than 7 years</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Lease must be substantively registered (LRA 2002 s 27(2)(b))</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Assignment (transfer) of unregistered leasehold with more than 7 years remaining</p></td>\n<td><p>Leasehold title registered for the first time on transfer</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Assent, vesting assent or vesting deed \u2014 freehold or leasehold with >7 yrs remaining</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Inheritance/estate administration dispositions trigger first registration</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Grant of a lease to take effect in possession more than 3 months after date of grant</p></td>\n<td><p>Future lease triggers registration requirement</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>First legal mortgage of freehold or leasehold with more than 7 years to run</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Mortgage triggers first registration of the underlying title</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h4 class=\"notes-h4\">TABLE 13 \u2014 All Leading Cases at a Glance</h4>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Case</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Topic</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Core Principle</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Bernstein of Leigh v Skyviews [1978]</p></td>\n<td><p>Airspace</p></td>\n<td><p>Landowner's rights in airspace limited to height necessary for ordinary use and enjoyment; upper airspace is free; aerial photography = no trespass</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Kelsen v Imperial Tobacco [1957]</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Lower airspace</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Advertising sign projecting inches into airspace above shop = trespass; injunction granted for removal</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Anchor Brewhouse v Berkley House [1987]</p></td>\n<td><p>Lower airspace</p></td>\n<td><p>Crane jib swinging over claimant's land = trespass in lower airspace; injunction granted</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Laiqat v Majid [2005]</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Lower airspace</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Extractor fan duct projecting into neighbour's airspace = trespass; lower airspace intrusion actionable</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Grigsby v Melville [1974]</p></td>\n<td><p>Ground below</p></td>\n<td><p>Cellar beneath claimant's house belongs to claimant even though only accessible from defendant's property; conveyance passes everything beneath the surface</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Holland v Hodgson [1872]</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Fixtures \u2014 test</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Two-part test: (1) degree of annexation; (2) purpose of annexation. Looms bolted to floor = fixtures; individual loose blocks = chattels</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Berkley v Poulett [1977]</p></td>\n<td><p>Fixtures \u2014 purpose prevails</p></td>\n<td><p>Purpose of annexation takes priority over degree; statue enjoyed as a chattel in its own right = chattel despite being embedded</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>D'Eyncourt v Gregory [1866]</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Fixtures \u2014 architectural design</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Items incorporated into architectural design of building = fixtures even without firm physical fixing</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Leigh v Taylor [1902]</p></td>\n<td><p>Fixtures \u2014 purpose = chattel</p></td>\n<td><p>Tapestries fixed to wall for their own enjoyment = chattels; purpose was to enjoy them as tapestries, not to enhance the building</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Elitestone Ltd v Morris [1997]</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Fixtures \u2014 destruction test</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Structure that cannot be removed without demolition = deemed intended to form part of the land; fixture</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Botham v TSB Bank [1996]</p></td>\n<td><p>Fixtures \u2014 practical application</p></td>\n<td><p>Mortgagee sold contents on repossession; applied both limbs of Holland v Hodgson to classify items as fixtures or chattels</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Walsh v Lonsdale [1882]</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Estate contracts</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Binding contract + specific performance = equitable (proprietary) interest in land; \\\"equity regards as done that which ought to be done\\\"</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>McCausland v Duncan Lawrie [1997]</p></td>\n<td><p>Land contract variation</p></td>\n<td><p>Oral variation of a material term (completion date) void; any material variation must comply with all s 2 LP(MP)A 1989 formalities</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Coatsworth v Johnson [1886\u201390]</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Equitable remedies</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Tenant who breached contract terms denied specific performance and equitable lease; \\\"must come to equity with clean hands\\\"</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>3. Flashcard Q&A Pairs</strong></span></h2>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Question</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Answer</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>What is the statutory definition of \\\"land\\\"?</p></td>\n<td><p>LPA 1925 s 205(1)(ix): the surface; buildings or parts of buildings; other corporeal hereditaments (fixtures); and incorporeal hereditaments (the benefit of proprietary rights with no physical substance such as easements).</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What are the only two legal estates in English land law?</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Fee simple absolute in possession (freehold) \u2014 LPA 1925 s 1(1)(a); and term of years absolute (leasehold) \u2014 LPA 1925 s 1(1)(b). All other estates take effect only in equity.</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>What does \\\"fee simple absolute in possession\\\" mean?</p></td>\n<td><p>\\\"Fee\\\" = inheritable. \\\"Simple\\\" = inheritable by any heir including distant relatives. \\\"Absolute\\\" = not determinable prematurely (no condition). \\\"In possession\\\" = current right to use and enjoyment (includes receiving rent if the land is let).</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What is the difference between a proprietary right and a personal right?</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Proprietary: enforceable in rem \u2014 can recover use/possession; binds third parties (if protected). Personal: enforceable in personam \u2014 damages only; cannot bind third parties (e.g. a licence).</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>What determines whether a right is proprietary or personal?</p></td>\n<td><p>Three factors: (1) Nature of the right \u2014 must be on the closed list; (2) Creation \u2014 must comply with correct formalities; (3) Protection \u2014 must be registered/protected to bind third parties.</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What are the three legal interests capable of existing under LPA 1925 s 1(2)?</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Easements granted for equivalent of freehold/leasehold duration (s 1(2)(a)); mortgages (s 1(2)(c)); rights of entry/forfeiture (s 1(2)(e)).</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>What is the maxim on the physical extent of land ownership and how is it qualified?</p></td>\n<td><p>\\\"Cuius est solum eius est usque coelum et ad inferos.\\\" Qualified for airspace: rights only extend to height necessary for ordinary use and enjoyment (Bernstein v Skyviews). Upper airspace is free. Qualified for ground: exceptions for Crown minerals, treasure (Treasure Act 1996), coal (Coal Act 1938) and deep drilling >300m (Infrastructure Act 2015 s 43).</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What is the Holland v Hodgson two-part test for fixtures?</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>(1) Degree of annexation \u2014 how firmly fixed; the more firmly, the more likely a fixture. (2) Purpose of annexation \u2014 if for the better enjoyment of the chattel as a chattel \u2192 chattel; if to enhance the land/building \u2192 fixture. Purpose prevails over degree (Berkley v Poulett [1977]).</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>When does a chattel always become a fixture?</p></td>\n<td><p>When it cannot be removed from the land without destruction or demolition \u2014 it is deemed intended to form part of the land (Elitestone Ltd v Morris [1997]).</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What are the formalities for a valid land contract under s 2 LP(MP)A 1989?</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>(1) In writing; (2) contains all expressly agreed terms (can be by reference); (3) signed by both parties. Oral contracts for land are void. Material variations must also comply with all three requirements (McCausland v Duncan Lawrie [1997]).</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>What is the proprietary effect of a binding land contract?</p></td>\n<td><p>It creates an equitable proprietary interest in the land \u2014 an estate contract. Equity regards as done that which ought to be done. Requires: valid s 2 LP(MP)A 1989 document + specific performance must be available (Walsh v Lonsdale [1882]).</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What are the three types of estate contract?</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Contract to buy land (binds seller; buyer has equitable interest between exchange and completion); option agreement (buyer can require seller to sell; seller must sell if notice served in time); right of pre-emption (first refusal if owner decides to sell; owner not obliged to sell).</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>What are the three stages of a freehold transfer and when does legal title pass?</p></td>\n<td><p>(1) Exchange of contracts (s 2 LP(MP)A 1989); (2) completion by deed (s 52(1) LPA 1925; s 1 LP(MP)A 1989); (3) registration (LRA 2002 s 27). For registered land: title passes only on registration. For unregistered land: title passes on completion; must register within 2 months or title reverts (ss 4 and 6 LRA 2002).</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What are the three principles of land registration?</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Mirror (register reflects all interests \u2014 hindered by overriding interests); Curtain (trust interests kept off register \u2014 simplifies conveyancing; achieved by restriction); Insurance (state guarantees accuracy; Sch 8 para 1 LRA 2002 \u2014 state indemnity for errors).</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>What are the three parts of a registered title?</p></td>\n<td><p>Property register: description, estate type, rights benefitting the land. Proprietorship register: owner's details, restrictions, class of title. Charges register: burdens, leases, mortgages, covenants, equitable easements.</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What are the four classes of registered title and which is best?</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Absolute (best \u2014 only bound by registered/overriding interests; state guarantee); Good Leasehold (satisfied as to leasehold only \u2014 freehold title not verified); Qualified (defect identified \u2014 rare); Possessory (adverse possession or no title deeds \u2014 may be bound by pre-registration interests).</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Why does the mirror principle fail?</p></td>\n<td><p>Because of overriding interests (LRA 2002 Sch 3) \u2014 interests that bind a purchaser without appearing on the register at all, e.g. legal leases of 7 years or less (Sch 3 para 1) and interests of persons in actual occupation (Sch 3 para 2).</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>What is the clean hands rule in equity (Coatsworth v Johnson)?</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Equitable remedies (specific performance, injunction) are discretionary and will be refused where the claimant has acted improperly or breached their own obligations. A tenant who breached the terms of a lease contract was denied specific performance and an equitable lease.</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<h2 class=\"notes-h2\"><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>4. Common Exam Pitfalls & Tricky Distinctions</strong></span></h2>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\">\n<thead><tr>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Pitfall / Distinction</strong></p></th>\n<th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Explanation</strong></p></th>\n</tr></thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><p>All physical land is owned by the Crown \u2014 not private owners</p></td>\n<td><p>A fundamental but easily forgotten point: in English law, all physical land is ultimately owned by the Crown. What private individuals own is an estate in land \u2014 a right to possess the land. This explains why land reverts to the Crown (bona vacantia) when a freehold owner dies without heirs or a will. Never say a private person \\\"owns the land\\\" \u2014 they own an estate in it.</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Purpose of annexation prevails over degree \u2014 Berkley v Poulett</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Students often overstate the degree of annexation limb. Berkley v Poulett confirms that purpose of annexation takes priority \u2014 a firmly embedded statue that is enjoyed as a chattel in its own right remains a chattel. Always move quickly to the purpose limb and make it the decisive factor. D'Eyncourt v Gregory shows the opposite: items loosely placed that form part of the architectural design = fixtures.</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Legal title in registered land passes on REGISTRATION \u2014 not completion</p></td>\n<td><p>For registered land, completing the deed does NOT transfer legal title. Title only passes once the buyer is registered as proprietor (LRA 2002 s 27(1)). Between completion and registration, the buyer has an equitable interest only. For unregistered land, title passes on completion of the deed \u2014 but must be registered within 2 months.</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Land contract variations: s 2 LP(MP)A 1989 applies to ALL material terms</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>McCausland v Duncan Lawrie: it is not enough to comply with s 2 formalities for the original contract if a later variation of a material term is made orally or informally. Any material variation requires: writing, all agreed terms, and signature of both parties. A term is material if it is essential to the nature of the contract (e.g. completion date, price).</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Equitable remedies are discretionary \u2014 not available as of right</p></td>\n<td><p>Unlike common law damages (available as of right), specific performance and injunctions are equitable and discretionary. The court considers the conduct of both parties. The clean hands maxim applies: a party who has breached their own obligations (Coatsworth v Johnson) will be denied equitable relief even if they have a valid contractual claim. Always flag this in equity-based questions.</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Airspace: upper vs lower is the key distinction</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Bernstein v Skyviews only protects the owner's lower airspace \u2014 that portion necessary for the ordinary use and enjoyment of the land. Upper airspace (above that height) belongs to no one. The boundary is not fixed by height in metres \u2014 it depends on the \\\"reasonable enjoyment\\\" of the particular piece of land. Do not say that all overflying is a trespass.</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>Lower airspace intrusion is trespass regardless of harm</p></td>\n<td><p>Once an object (sign, crane jib, duct) intrudes into the lower airspace of a property, it is a trespass \u2014 even if it causes no actual damage (Kelsen; Anchor Brewhouse; Laiqat v Majid). This contrasts with nuisance, which requires actual interference with enjoyment. An injunction can be obtained to compel removal even without proof of harm.</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>The mirror principle is imperfect \u2014 overriding interests are the key exception</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Do not state the mirror principle as an absolute truth. The register is supposed to reflect all interests, but overriding interests (LRA 2002 Sch 3) bind purchasers without appearing on it. The LRA 2002 retains overriding interests \\\"in limited form\\\" \u2014 mainly to protect those who cannot reasonably be expected to register (short-term tenants; people in actual occupation). Always acknowledge this qualification when discussing the mirror principle.</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><p>A right of pre-emption is weaker than an option \u2014 do not conflate them</p></td>\n<td><p>An option gives the holder the right to compel the owner to sell at any time during the option period. A right of pre-emption only gives first refusal if the owner decides to sell \u2014 the owner is not obliged to sell at all. A right of pre-emption holder cannot force a sale; an option holder can. Both are estate contracts, but they confer very different powers.</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Fixtures pass automatically with the land under s 62 LPA 1925</p></td>\n<td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Once an item is classified as a fixture, it passes automatically with the land on sale by virtue of s 62 LPA 1925, unless it is specifically excluded under s 62(4). A seller cannot remove a fixture after exchange of contracts. The standard protection is to complete a TA10 fixtures and contents form to agree precisely which items are included or excluded. If the contract is silent, the fixture stays.</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>"}], "Mortgages": [{"id": "mortgages-notes", "title": "W2: Mortgages", "content": "<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>MORTGAGES \u2014 COMPREHENSIVE REVISION NOTES</strong></span></p>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>1. Structured Topic Overview</strong></span></h3>\n<p>Mortgages analysis proceeds through five logical stages:</p>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>STAGE 1 \u2014 CREATION &amp; CLASSIFICATION</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>Identify if the mortgage is legal or equitable</li><li>Legal: deed (LPA s 52; LP(MP)A 1989 s 1) + substantive registration (LRA 2002 s 27(2)(f))</li><li>Equitable: mortgage of equitable interest (LPA s 53(1)(c)); or defective legal mortgage treated as contract (LP(MP)A 1989 s 2)</li></ul>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>STAGE 2 \u2014 EQUITY OF REDEMPTION: BORROWER PROTECTIONS</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>Right to redeem: no clog or fetter on the equity of redemption</li><li>Postponement of redemption date: void if makes mortgage effectively irredeemable (Fairclough); upheld if borrower gets real benefit and will recover full asset (Knightsbridge)</li><li>Options to purchase: generally void if granted simultaneously with mortgage (Samuel v Jarrah); may survive if genuinely independent transaction (Reeve v Lisle; Warnborough v Garmite)</li><li>Collateral advantages: struck out if unconscionable, penal, or repugnant to right to redeem; solus ties valid if they end within the mortgage term (Biggs v Hoddinott; Noakes v Rice)</li><li>Unconscionable terms: court strikes out if imposed in morally reprehensible manner (Multiservice test); high interest rate may be unconscionable (Cityland)</li></ul>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>STAGE 3 \u2014 UNDUE INFLUENCE</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>Two types: overt coercion; or exploitation of trust/ascendancy (RBS v Etridge (No 2))</li><li>Relationship presumptions: irrebuttable (solicitor/client, doctor/patient etc); none for husband/wife or adult child \u2014 must prove</li><li>Risk to lender: mortgage unenforceable if undue influence proved (Barclays v O&#x27;Brien)</li><li>Bank put on inquiry in non-commercial surety situations; must follow Etridge guidelines to protect itself</li></ul>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>STAGE 4 \u2014 PRIORITY OF MORTGAGES (REGISTERED LAND)</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>Legal: priority by order of registration (LRA 2002 s 48)</li><li>Equitable: priority by order of creation (s 28); protected by notice on charges register (s 32)</li><li>Unprotected equitable mortgage loses priority to subsequent registered disposition for value (s 29(1))</li><li>Priority can be altered by deed of priority / intercreditor deed (must be registered)</li></ul>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>STAGE 5 \u2014 LENDER&#x27;S REMEDIES</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>Debt action (personal; used for shortfall / negative equity)</li><li>Possession: right arises on execution of mortgage deed (Four Maids); residential \u2014 court must consider AJA 1970 s 36 postponement; &quot;reasonable period&quot; = remainder of mortgage term (Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester v Norgan)</li><li>Sale: power arises when mortgage money due (LPA s 101(1)(i)); exercisable on any s 103 LPA criterion; duty to obtain true market value (Cuckmere); unfettered discretion as to timing (Silven Properties)</li><li>Receiver: agent of borrower (lender not liable for negligence); duty of due diligence subject to paying off debt</li><li>Foreclosure: rare; court usually orders sale in lieu; extinguishes other mortgages and contractual debt</li></ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>2. Summary Revision Tables</strong></span></h3>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 1 \u2014 Key Definitions &amp; Statutory Provisions</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Concept</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Definition / Provision</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Source</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Mortgage</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Security interest in land given by borrower (mortgagor) to lender (mortgagee) in exchange for a loan</p></td><td><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Mortgagor</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>The borrower who grants the mortgage over their land</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Mortgagee</strong></span></p></td><td><p>The lender who receives the mortgage as security</p></td><td><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Legal date of redemption</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Contractual date on which loan must be repaid in full (historically the one and only date)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Historical / general law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Equitable right to redeem</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Equitable intervention: borrower may repay at any time after the legal date of redemption passes</p></td><td><p>Equity / Toomes v Conset [1745]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Equity of redemption</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Bundle of rights protecting the borrower as true owner of property; financial value = market value minus outstanding debt</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Equity</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Clog/fetter</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Any term which prevents or unreasonably restricts the exercise of the equity of redemption</p></td><td><p>Equity</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Collateral advantage</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Extra benefit extracted by lender beyond repayment of capital and interest; potentially void if unconscionable</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Equity</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Solus tie</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Condition requiring borrower to purchase all supplies from lender (e.g. brewery tie)</p></td><td><p>Noakes v Rice; Biggs v Hoddinott</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Power of sale</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Lender&#x27;s right to sell mortgaged property on borrower&#x27;s default</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>LPA 1925 s 101(1)(i)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Receiver</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Agent appointed to manage mortgaged property and collect income towards debt; deemed agent of borrower</p></td><td><p>LPA 1925 s 101(1)(iii)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Foreclosure</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Historic remedy: freehold vests in lender in satisfaction of debt; extinguishes other charges and contractual debt</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>General law</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 2 \u2014 Legal vs Equitable Mortgages</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Feature</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Legal Mortgage</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Equitable Mortgage</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Creation basis</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Granted over legal estate by legal owner</p></td><td><p>Mortgage of equitable interest; OR defective legal mortgage</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Formality requirement</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Deed (LPA s 52; LP(MP)A 1989 s 1)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Writing + signature (LPA s 53(1)(c)); OR s 2 LP(MP)A 1989 for defective legal mortgage</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Registration</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Must be substantively registered (LRA 2002 s 27(2)(f)) to take effect as legal mortgage</p></td><td><p>Protected by notice on charges register (LRA 2002 s 32)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Effect of non-registration</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Does not take effect as legal mortgage (s 27(1)) but may be equitable</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Unprotected equitable mortgage loses priority to subsequent registered disposition for value (s 29(1))</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Remedies available</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Debt action; possession; sale; receiver; foreclosure</p></td><td><p>Debt action; foreclosure; receiver; cannot generally possess or sell without court order</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Priority</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>By order of registration (LRA 2002 s 48)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>By order of creation (LRA 2002 s 28)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Inherently equitable</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Cannot be \u2014 if term certain, it can be legal</p></td><td><p>Yes \u2014 where mortgage of equitable interest (LPA s 53(1)(c))</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 3 \u2014 Equity of Redemption: Borrower Protections</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Protection</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Cases</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>No clog/fetter on equity of redemption</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Core principle: a mortgage must always be redeemable; any term preventing redemption altogether is void</p></td><td><p>Toomes v Conset [1745]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Postponement of redemption \u2014 VOID</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Struck out where term effectively makes mortgage irredeemable (leasehold asset nearly exhausted; borrower recovers nothing of value)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Fairclough v Swan Brewery [1912]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Postponement of redemption \u2014 VALID</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Upheld where: freehold asset (enduring); borrower receives real benefit (e.g. low interest rate); borrower will recover full asset; freely agreed commercial bargain</p></td><td><p>Knightsbridge Estates v Byrne [1939]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Option to purchase \u2014 generally VOID</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Option granted simultaneously with mortgage usually invalid \u2014 prevents borrower recovering property free of debt</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Samuel v Jarrah Timber [1904]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Option to purchase \u2014 may be VALID</strong></span></p></td><td><p>If granted in subsequent independent transaction, may be upheld; court looks at &quot;substance of transaction&quot;</p></td><td><p>Reeve v Lisle [1902]; Warnborough v Garmite [2003]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Collateral advantage \u2014 VOID</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Struck out if unconscionable, penal, or repugnant to equitable right to redeem, OR if it extends beyond the mortgage term</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Noakes &amp; Co v Rice [1902]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Collateral advantage \u2014 VALID</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Upheld if it ends within the mortgage term and is not unconscionable or oppressive; lender may gain collateral advantage</p></td><td><p>Biggs v Hoddinott [1898]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Unconscionable terms</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Court strikes out if imposed in &quot;morally reprehensible manner&quot;; mere unfairness insufficient; imbalance of bargaining power and exploitation relevant</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Cityland v Dabrah [1968]; Multiservice Bookbinding v Marden [1979]</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 4 \u2014 Unconscionable Interest Rate: Key Cases</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Case</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Outcome</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Principle</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Cityland</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> v </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Dabrah</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> [1968]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Void \u2014 reduced to 7%</p></td><td><p>Clear imbalance of bargaining power; borrower threatened with homelessness; ~38% effective rate including premium was unconscionable</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Multiservice Bookbinding v Marden [1979]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Valid \u2014 not unconscionable</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Term linked to Swiss franc value; equality of bargaining power; borrower entered bad bargain with eyes open; no moral reprehensibility</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Falco Finance v Gough</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Void</p></td><td><p>Penalty interest on default far exceeding lender&#x27;s actual losses is void</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Davies v Directloans [1986]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Valid</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Higher interest justified by poor credit history of borrower; lender not acting improperly</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Paragon Finance v Nash [2002]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Valid (with limits)</p></td><td><p>Lender may charge higher rate due to own financial difficulties; must not exercise discretion for improper purpose</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 5 \u2014 Undue Influence</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Issue</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Two types (RBS v </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Etridge</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> (No 2) [2002])</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Type 1: Overt improper pressure / coercion / unlawful threats. Type 2: One party has influence or ascendancy over the other, which is taken advantage of</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Irrebuttable presumption of influence</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Parent/child; guardian/ward; trustee/beneficiary; solicitor/client; doctor/patient</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>No presumption (must be proved)</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Husband and wife; parent and adult child \u2014 influence must be positively shown</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Proof required</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>(1) Relationship of trust and confidence; (2) Transaction that calls for explanation \u2014 e.g. suspiciously high value or not in the surety&#x27;s interest</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Effect on mortgage</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Mortgage unenforceable against the party unduly influenced; their interest ranks above the lender&#x27;s (Barclays v O&#x27;Brien [1994])</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>When lender is put on inquiry</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Any non-commercial setting where one person stands as surety for another (RBS v Etridge)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Exception: joint benefit</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Lender NOT put on inquiry if purpose of loan is for joint benefit of co-owners (CIBC Mortgages v Pitt [1994])</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Limits on equitable relief</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Delay defeats equity (claimant must act promptly); claimant must come with clean hands</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 6 \u2014 </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Etridge</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> Guidelines (RBS v </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Etridge</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> (No 2) [2002])</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Party</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Required Steps</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>The Bank</strong></span></p></td><td><p>(1) Write to the surety (not through the business owner) explaining it requires confirmation from an independent solicitor that the transaction has been explained; (2) ask the surety to nominate an independent solicitor and provide that solicitor with all relevant information; (3) do not proceed until it receives the solicitor&#x27;s certificate</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>The Independent Solicitor</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>(1) Meet the surety face-to-face and alone (not with the business owner); (2) explain why they have come (to prevent future undue influence claim); (3) explain the documents and transaction in plain language; (4) point out the risks; (5) emphasise the surety has a choice; (6) keep detailed attendance note and confirm in writing; (7) send certificate to the bank</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 7 \u2014 Priority of Mortgages (Registered Land)</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Type</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Priority Rule</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Protection / Consequence</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Legal mortgage</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Priority by order of registration (LRA 2002 s 48) \u2014 not by order of execution of mortgage deeds</p></td><td><p>Must be substantively registered (s 27(2)(f)); simultaneous registration \u2014 application specifies order</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Equitable mortgage (protected)</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Priority by order of creation (LRA 2002 s 28) \u2014 notice does not change priority, only protects it</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Enter notice on charges register (LRA 2002 s 32); binding on subsequent purchasers (s 29(2))</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Equitable mortgage (unprotected)</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Loses priority to any subsequent registrable disposition for value \u2014 including legal mortgage or transfer of legal estate</p></td><td><p>Not binding on purchaser for valuable consideration (s 29(1))</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Deed of priority</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Lenders may agree to alter the statutory priority position</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Must be registered at Land Registry to be effective</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Occupier&#x27;s rights</strong></span></p></td><td><p>If occupier&#x27;s rights not postponed to lender&#x27;s interest, lender cannot take possession to exercise power of sale</p></td><td><p>Waiver/postponement clause required; important to enforce security</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 8 \u2014 Lender&#x27;s Remedies: Overview</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Remedy</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Legal / Equitable?</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Rule</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Authority</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Debt action</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Both</p></td><td><p>Personal contractual claim; rarely used in isolation; used for shortfall after sale (negative equity)</p></td><td><p>\u2014</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Possession</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Legal only as of right</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Right arises on execution of mortgage deed (even before default); residential \u2014 court may postpone under AJA 1970 s 36</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Four Maids v Dudley Marshall [1957]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Sale</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Legal only as of right (equitable needs court)</p></td><td><p>Power arises: mortgage money due (s 101(1)(i)); exercisable: one s 103 criterion met; surplus = trustee for borrower (s 105)</p></td><td><p>Cuckmere Brick v Mutual Finance [1971]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Receiver</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Both</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Deemed agent of borrower; lender not liable for receiver&#x27;s negligence; duty of due diligence subject to paying off debt</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>LPA 1925 s 101(1)(iii)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Foreclosure</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Both</p></td><td><p>Rare; court usually orders sale in lieu; extinguishes other charges and borrower&#x27;s contractual debt; borrower can re-open case</p></td><td><p>Law Commission recommends abolition</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 9 \u2014 Power of Sale: Arises vs Exercisable (LPA 1925)</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Stage</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Notes</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Power ARISES</strong></span></p></td><td><p>When mortgage money has become due (LPA s 101(1)(i))</p></td><td><p>Capital &amp; interest: as soon as one payment is due (Payne v Cardiff [1932]). Interest only: at legal redemption date (usually ~6 months from start)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Power EXERCISABLE \u2014 s 103(</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>i</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>)</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Notice requiring repayment of whole loan served + default</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Lender can demand full repayment at any time \u2014 no arrears required</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Power EXERCISABLE \u2014 s 103(ii)</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Interest in arrears for at least two months</p></td><td><p>Not two full months&#x27; worth \u2014 any interest outstanding for two months suffices</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Power EXERCISABLE \u2014 s 103(iii)</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Breach of another mortgage covenant (e.g. insure; keep in repair)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Must affect the value of the security</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Sale after power arises but before exercisable</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Sale to innocent purchaser is valid; lender is liable in damages to borrower</p></td><td><p>LPA 1925 s 104</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Equitable mortgagee&#x27;s power of sale</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No statutory power; must apply to court under TOLATA 1996 s 14</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>\u2014</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 10 \u2014 Lender&#x27;s Duties on Sale: Key Cases</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Case</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Facts (brief)</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Principle</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Cuckmere Brick v Mutual Finance [1971]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Lender failed to disclose planning permission in sale particulars</p></td><td><p>Duty to take reasonable care to obtain &quot;true market value&quot; / &quot;proper price&quot;; damages = price difference</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Michael v Miller [2004]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Sale price within range \u00a31.6m-\u00a31.9m; received \u00a31.625m</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Perfection of price not required; no liability if price within acceptable margin of error</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Tse Kwong Lam v Wong Chit Sen [1983]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Lender sold to company owned by lender&#x27;s family via auction</p></td><td><p>Lender must take expert advice on sale method, marketing and reserve price; courts scrutinise sales to parties connected with the lender</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Silven Properties v RBS [2004]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Borrower argued lender should have delayed sale to improve property/await planning permission</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Lender has &quot;unfettered discretion&quot; as to when to sell; no duty to delay sale or improve property before selling</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 11 \u2014 AJA 1970 s 36: Court&#x27;s Power to Postpone Possession</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Issue</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Scope</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Applies where property is wholly or partly residential (need not be borrower&#x27;s main home); only triggered by a court possession action</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Test for postponement</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Court must be satisfied borrower is likely to be able to repay sums due (or remedy default) within a &quot;reasonable period&quot;</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>&quot;Reasonable period&quot;</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Remainder of the mortgage term (Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester BS v Norgan [1996])</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What court can do</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Adjourn possession proceedings; stay or postpone execution of possession order; impose conditions on postponement</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What court CANNOT do</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Prevent lender exercising right to possess altogether; postpone where no court action brought (Ropaigelach v Barclays [2000]); prevent sale without court order (Horsham Properties v Clark [2009])</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>National &amp; Provincial BS v Lloyd [1996]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Borrower must present detailed financial plan showing how loan and arrears will be cleared before term expires</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Bristol &amp; West BS v Ellis [1996]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Postponement to allow self-sale: estate agent&#x27;s optimistic estimate insufficient; court must see sale proceeds will cover debt</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Target Home Loans v Clothier [1994]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Short 3-month postponement granted where genuine offer received from estate agent</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Mortgage Services v Steele [1996]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Court required firm evidence of imminent exchange; merely instructing solicitors insufficient; courts suspicious of delay tactics</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 12 \u2014 All Leading Cases </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>at a Glance</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Case</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Topic</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Core Principle</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Toomes v </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Conset</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> [1745]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Equity of redemption</p></td><td><p>Equity will not allow terms that prevent redemption altogether</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Fairclough v Swan Brewery [1912]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Postponement</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Postponement rendering mortgage effectively irredeemable (leasehold nearly exhausted) is void</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Knightsbridge Estates v Byrne [1939]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Postponement</p></td><td><p>40-year postponement on freehold upheld: borrower gets full asset back, received benefit (low interest), freely negotiated commercial deal</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Samuel v Jarrah Timber [1904]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Option to purchase</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Option granted simultaneously with mortgage generally void</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Reeve v Lisle [1902]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Option to purchase</p></td><td><p>Option in subsequent independent transaction may be upheld</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Warnborough</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> v </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Garmite</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> [2003]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Option to purchase</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Court looks at substance: same-day transactions can be genuinely separate; label irrelevant</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Noakes &amp; Co v Rice [1902]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Collateral advantage</p></td><td><p>Solus tie extending beyond mortgage term void \u2014 borrower would not recover free asset</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Biggs v Hoddinott [1898]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Collateral advantage</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Solus tie within mortgage term upheld \u2014 not unconscionable or oppressive</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Cityland</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> v </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Dabrah</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> [1968]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Unconscionable terms</p></td><td><p>Effective ~38% rate with exploitation of vulnerable borrower = unconscionable; reduced to 7%</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Multiservice Bookbinding v Marden [1979]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Unconscionable terms</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Swiss franc indexation upheld: equality of bargaining power; morally reprehensible test not met</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>RBS v </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Etridge</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> (No 2) [2002]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Undue influence</p></td><td><p>Defines two types of UI; bank put on inquiry in non-commercial surety; sets out Etridge guidelines</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Barclays Bank v O&#x27;Brien [1994]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Undue influence</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Successful UI claim renders mortgage unenforceable against surety; surety&#x27;s interest ranks above lender&#x27;s</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>CIBC Mortgages v Pitt [1994]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Undue influence</p></td><td><p>No inquiry where loan for joint benefit of both co-owners</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Four Maids v Dudley Marshall [1957]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Possession</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Right to possess arises immediately on execution of mortgage deed, &quot;before the ink is dry&quot;</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Ropaigelach</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> v Barclays [2000]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Possession (AJA s 36)</p></td><td><p>AJA s 36 cannot be used where lender exercises right to possess without court proceedings</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Horsham Properties v Clark [2009]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Sale</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Court cannot prevent lender from exercising power of sale without first obtaining a court order</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester BS v Norgan [1996]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Possession / s 36</p></td><td><p>&quot;Reasonable period&quot; for AJA s 36 purposes = remainder of the mortgage term</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Cuckmere Brick v Mutual Finance [1971]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Duty on sale</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Lender owes borrower duty to take reasonable care to obtain true market value / proper price</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Silven Properties v RBS [2004]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Duty on sale</p></td><td><p>Lender has unfettered discretion as to when to sell; no duty to delay or improve property first</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Tse Kwong Lam v Wong Chit Sen [1983]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Duty on sale</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Must take expert advice on sale method and reserve price; sale to connected party scrutinised closely</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Payne v Cardiff [1932]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Power of sale arises</p></td><td><p>Capital &amp; interest mortgage: power of sale arises on first missed payment</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>3. Flashcard Q&amp;A Pairs</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Question</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Answer</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What are the formalities for a legal mortgage?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Deed complying with LP(MP)A 1989 s 1 (LPA s 52); substantively registered at Land Registry (LRA 2002 s 27(2)(f)).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>When does a mortgage arise as equitable only?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>(1) Mortgage of equitable interest (LPA s 53(1)(c): writing + signature); or (2) Defective legal mortgage treated as estate contract (s 2 LP(MP)A 1989: writing, all terms, signed by both parties).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is the equity of redemption?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Bundle of equitable rights protecting the borrower as true owner; prevents exploitation by lender; financial value = market value minus outstanding debt.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is the test for an unconscionable mortgage term?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Was the term imposed in a &quot;morally reprehensible manner&quot; affecting the conscience of the party imposing it? (Multiservice Bookbinding v Marden) \u2014 mere unfairness or bad bargain is insufficient.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Fairclough vs Knightsbridge \u2014 why different outcomes on postponement?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Fairclough: leasehold (depreciating asset), borrower recovered virtually worthless lease \u2014 effectively irredeemable \u2192 VOID. Knightsbridge: freehold (enduring), borrower got full asset back and benefited from low interest rate \u2192 UPHELD.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>When is a solus tie valid as a collateral advantage?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>When it ends within the mortgage term and is not unconscionable or oppressive (Biggs v Hoddinott). Void if it extends beyond the mortgage term (Noakes v Rice).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>When is an option to purchase in a mortgage void?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>If granted simultaneously with the mortgage (Samuel v Jarrah). May survive if it is a genuinely independent subsequent transaction (Reeve v Lisle). Court looks at substance, not label (Warnborough v Garmite).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What are the two types of undue influence in RBS v </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Etridge</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>(1) Overt improper pressure/coercion/unlawful threats. (2) Exploitation of trust and ascendancy in a relationship.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Is there a presumption of undue influence between husband and wife?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>No \u2014 influence must be positively proved. Contrast: solicitor/client, doctor/patient etc. \u2014 irrebuttable presumption.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>When is a bank put on inquiry of undue influence?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Any non-commercial setting where one party stands as surety for another (Etridge). NOT where loan is for joint benefit of co-owners (CIBC v Pitt).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is the effect of a successful undue influence claim?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Mortgage unenforceable against the surety \u2014 their interest ranks above the lender&#x27;s; lender cannot possess or sell to recover debt against that person (Barclays v O&#x27;Brien).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>How does a bank protect itself from undue influence claims?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Follow Etridge guidelines: write to surety directly; require independent solicitor to meet surety alone, explain transaction and risks, confirm in writing; receive solicitor&#x27;s certificate before proceeding.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>How is priority determined between legal mortgages on registered land?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>By order of registration (LRA 2002 s 48) \u2014 not by order of execution of mortgage deeds.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>How is priority determined between equitable mortgages?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>By order of creation (LRA 2002 s 28). Notice on charges register does not change priority \u2014 it only protects the mortgage against subsequent purchasers (s 29(2)).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>When does the statutory power of sale arise (LPA s 101)?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>When the mortgage money has become due. For capital &amp; interest mortgages: when first payment is due (Payne v Cardiff). For interest-only: at the legal redemption date.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What are the three s 103 LPA 1925 criteria making the power of sale exercisable?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>(i) Notice to repay served + default; (ii) interest in arrears for 2+ months; (iii) breach of another mortgage covenant (e.g. insurance, repair).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What happens if lender sells after power arises but before it is exercisable?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Sale to innocent purchaser is valid (LPA s 104); lender is liable in damages to the borrower.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What duty does the lender owe when selling?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Duty to take reasonable care to obtain the true market value/proper price (Cuckmere Brick). Does not require perfection of price (Michael v Miller). Lender has unfettered discretion as to when to sell (Silven Properties).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is the lender&#x27;s position regarding timing of sale?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Unfettered discretion as to when to sell; no duty to delay sale, improve property, or await a better market (Silven Properties v RBS [2004]).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What does AJA 1970 s 36 allow the court to do?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Adjourn possession proceedings or postpone execution of possession order, if borrower likely to repay within a &quot;reasonable period&quot; (= remainder of mortgage term: Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester v Norgan). Applies only if lender brings a court action; cannot prevent sale.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is a receiver and why does it benefit the lender?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Manager of mortgaged property; power under LPA s 101(1)(iii); deemed agent of borrower \u2014 lender therefore not liable for the receiver&#x27;s negligence; receiver applies income to outstanding debt.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What are the advantages of foreclosure for the borrower?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Extinguishes all other mortgages on the property AND extinguishes the contractual debt \u2014 lender cannot sue for any shortfall exceeding property value.</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>4. Common Exam Pitfalls &amp; Tricky Distinctions</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Pitfall / Distinction</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Explanation</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Conflating when power of sale ARISES vs when it is EXERCISABLE</strong></span></p></td><td><p>These are two distinct questions under LPA 1925. Arises: when mortgage money is due (s 101). Exercisable: only when a s 103 criterion is met. A sale after power has arisen but before exercisable is valid against an innocent purchaser (s 104) but the lender is liable in damages to the borrower. Never skip this two-stage analysis.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Fairclough vs Knightsbridge \u2014 do not over-generalise</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>The key distinction is: leasehold (depreciating asset) vs freehold (enduring asset), and whether the borrower genuinely benefits and recovers the full asset. Do not treat all long postponements as void or all commercial deals as valid \u2014 always apply these specific factors.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Collateral advantages: the solus tie timing rule</strong></span></p></td><td><p>A solus tie within the mortgage term may be valid (Biggs v Hoddinott); one extending beyond the mortgage term is void (Noakes v Rice). Always check when the tie expires relative to the mortgage term \u2014 this is the critical distinction.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Options to purchase: label does not determine outcome</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Warnborough v Garmite: court looks at the &quot;substance of the transaction,&quot; not the label. A same-day option and mortgage can both survive if genuinely independent. Samuel v Jarrah: option given as part of mortgage deal = void. Do not assume that merely separating documents makes them independent.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Unconscionable terms \u2014 not mere unfairness</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Multiservice Bookbinding: the term must have been imposed in a &quot;morally reprehensible manner.&quot; A bad bargain freely entered by a party with equal bargaining power is not unconscionable. Cityland: the crucial factor was exploitation of a vulnerable borrower. High interest alone is not enough without examining the circumstances.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Undue influence: no presumption for spouses</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Husband and wife relationship carries NO presumption of undue influence \u2014 the party alleging UI must positively prove trust, confidence, and exploitation. Only the specific relationships listed (solicitor/client etc.) carry irrebuttable presumption.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>AJA 1970 s 36: cannot prevent sale; cannot help if no court action</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Ropaigelach: s 36 only applies if the lender brings a court possession action \u2014 a lender who physically takes possession or exercises power of sale without going to court sidesteps s 36 entirely. Horsham Properties: court cannot prevent lender from exercising power of sale without court order.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Priority: notice does not change order \u2014 it only protects</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>For equitable mortgages, priority is determined by order of creation (s 28). Entering a notice on the charges register does not promote the equitable mortgage above an earlier one \u2014 it merely protects the mortgage from being defeated by a subsequent purchaser for value.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Receiver is agent of borrower, not lender</strong></span></p></td><td><p>This is the reason lenders prefer receivers to direct management: lender is not liable for the receiver&#x27;s negligence. Do not confuse this with the receiver acting in the lender&#x27;s interests \u2014 the receiver&#x27;s main duty is paying off the mortgage debt.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Equitable mortgagee&#x27;s remedies are narrower</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Equitable mortgagees generally cannot possess or sell as of right \u2014 they need a court order (apply under TOLATA 1996 s 14). Legal mortgagees have the statutory power of sale under LPA s 101. This distinction can be outcome-determinative on a problem question.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>The &quot;morally reprehensible&quot; test \u2014 apply the factors</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Courts look at: circumstances in which term was imposed; relative bargaining power; whether borrower was exploited or made an informed decision; whether the imposition &quot;affected the conscience&quot; of the party imposing it. Apply Cityland (unconscionable) and Multiservice (not unconscionable) as contrasting examples and always reach a reasoned conclusion.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Postponement of possession: standard of evidence required</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Courts are suspicious of borrowers using postponement applications to delay. National &amp; Provincial: detailed financial plan required. Bristol &amp; West: optimistic estate agent estimate insufficient. Target Home Loans: genuine offer acceptable for short postponement. Mortgage Services v Steele: imminent exchange of contracts required for sale-based postponement.</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>"}], "Easements": [{"id": "easements-notes", "title": "W3/4: Easements", "content": "<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>EASEMENTS \u2014 COMPREHENSIVE REVISION NOTES</strong></span></p>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>1. Structured Topic Overview</strong></span></h3>\n<p>Easements analysis follows a strict logical sequence. An examiner expects you to work through each stage in order:</p>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>STAGE 1 \u2014 NATURE &amp; CLASSIFICATION</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>Define easement: proprietary right to use another&#x27;s land</li><li>Classify as legal (LPA s 1(2)(a): freehold/leasehold duration) or equitable (LPA s 1(3))</li><li>Identify positive vs negative; distinguish from licences, profits \u00e0 prendre, restrictive covenants, public rights, quasi-easements</li></ul>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>S</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>TAGE 2 \u2014 CAPABILITY: Re Ellenborough Park [1956] TEST</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>(i) Dominant &amp; servient tenement must exist</li><li>(ii) Right must accommodate the dominant tenement</li><li>(iii) No common ownership of the two tenements</li><li>(iv) Right must lie in grant</li></ul>\n<p><strong>T</strong><strong>hen check the three DISQUALIFYING FACTORS:</strong></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>No exclusive possession (Batchelor v Marlow ouster test; Moncrieff possession &amp; control)</li><li>No additional expenditure required from servient owner</li><li>No ongoing permission required</li></ul>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>S</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>TAGE 3 \u2014 ACQUISITION</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>Express: deed + registration (s 52 LPA; s 27(2)(d) LRA 2002)</li><li>Implied \u2014 Necessity (landlocked land only)</li><li>Implied \u2014 Common intention (specific purpose; Wong v Beaumont)</li><li>Implied \u2014 Wheeldon v Burrows (grant only; continuous &amp; apparent; necessary for reasonable enjoyment)</li><li>Implied \u2014 s 62 LPA 1925 (grant only; prior diversity OR continuous &amp; apparent)</li><li>Prescription \u2014 Common law / Lost Modern Grant / PA 1832 (20+ years; nec vi, nec clam, nec precario)</li></ul>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>S</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>TAGE 4 \u2014 ENFORCEABILITY</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>Legal easements: registered land = substantive registration; unregistered = binds world</li><li>Implied legal: overriding under Sch 3 para 3 LRA 2002 (knowledge / obvious / exercised within 1 yr)</li><li>Equitable easements: registered = notice on charges register (s 32 LRA); unregistered = Class D(iii) Land Charge</li></ul>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>S</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>TAGE 5 \u2014 REMEDIES</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>Prohibitory injunction; damages; mandatory injunction to remove obstruction</li></ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>2. Summary Revision Tables</strong></span></h3>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 1 \u2014 Key Definitions &amp; Statutory Provisions</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Concept</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Definition / Provision</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Source</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Easement</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Proprietary right to use land belonging to another</p></td><td><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Dominant tenement</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Land benefitting from the easement</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Re Ellenborough Park</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Servient tenement</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Land burdened by the easement</p></td><td><p>Re Ellenborough Park</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Grant</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Seller/landlord gives buyer/tenant an easement over retained land</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Reservation</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Seller/landlord retains a right over the land sold/leased; strictly construed</p></td><td><p>Cordell v Second Clanfield [1969]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Quasi-easement</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Right exercised by owner over their own land \u2014 potential easement if land divided</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Legal easement</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Duration equivalent to fee simple absolute or term of years absolute</p></td><td><p>LPA 1925 s 1(2)(a)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Equitable easement</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>All other easements \u2014 uncertain term or failed legal formalities</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>LPA 1925 s 1(3)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Profit \u00e0 prendre</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Right to take produce/animals/minerals from servient land \u2014 distinct from easement</p></td><td><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Licence</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Personal right to use land; not proprietary; not enforceable against third parties</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>General law</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 2 \u2014 Re Ellenborough Park [1956]: Capability Test</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Requirement</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule / Detail</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Authority</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>1. Dominant &amp; servient tenement</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Two identifiable pieces of land; easement cannot exist &quot;in gross&quot;</p></td><td><p>London &amp; Blenheim Estates v Ladbroke [1992]; Hawkins v Rutter [1892]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>2. Accommodates dominant tenement</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Direct beneficial impact on the land \u2014 not merely on the business carried on there (unless nexus between land and business)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Hill v Tupper [1863]; Moody v Steggles [1879]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>  Proximity</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Dominant &amp; servient need not adjoin but must be sufficiently proximate</p></td><td><p>Pugh v Savage [1970]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>3. No common ownership</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Must be owned by different persons; easement extinguished if land reunited in common ownership</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Roe v Siddons [1888]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>4. Lies in grant</strong></span></p></td><td><p>(a) Capable grantor &amp; grantee (18+, owns legal estate; body must not fluctuate) (b) Reasonably exact description (c) Judicially recognised right</p></td><td><p>William Aldred&#x27;s Case [1610]; Dyce v Lady James Hay [1852]</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 3 \u2014 Disqualifying Factors</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Disqualifying Factor</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Authority</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Exclusive possession (ouster)</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Right disqualified if servient owner left with no reasonable use of the land</p></td><td><p>Batchelor v Marlow [2003]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Exclusive possession (possession &amp; control)</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Persuasive alternative: disqualified only if servient owner loses ultimate possession &amp; control (Scottish law)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Moncrieff v Jamieson [2007]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Applied test (English courts)</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Servient owner can do anything on land except interfere with the right \u2192 not disqualified</p></td><td><p>Kettel v Bloomfold Ltd [2012]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Additional expenditure</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Right disqualified if servient owner must spend money to enable enjoyment of the right; dominant owner may enter to carry out repairs at own expense</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Jones v Pritchard [1908]; Regis Property v Redman [1956]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Permission</strong></span></p></td><td><p>If dominant owner must seek permission each time right is exercised \u2192 only a licence, not an easement</p></td><td><p>Green v Ashco Horticultural [1966]</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 4 \u2014 Judicially Recognised Easements (Non-Exhaustive List)</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Right</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Notes</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Authority</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Right of way</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Classic recognised easement</p></td><td><p>Borman v Griffiths [1930]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Drainage / pipelines</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Through pipes across servient land</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Atwood v Bovis Homes [2001]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Support</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Right to have buildings supported by neighbouring land</p></td><td><p>Dalton v Angus &amp; Co [1881]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Storage</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Use of shed or storage space on servient land</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Wright v Macadam [1949]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Parking</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Provided ouster test not breached</p></td><td><p>Kettel v Bloomfold Ltd [2012]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Sporting/leisure facilities</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Use of communal recreational facilities</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Regency Villas v Diamond Resorts [2018]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Recreational use of park</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Foundation of Re Ellenborough Park itself</p></td><td><p>Re Ellenborough Park [1956]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>New rights</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>List not closed \u2014 new easements possible if not negative in character</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Dyce v Lady James Hay [1852]; Phipps v Pears [1965]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>NOT: scenic view</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Too vague; not capable of reasonably exact description</p></td><td><p>William Aldred&#x27;s Case [1610]</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 5 \u2014 Methods of Acquisition: Comparison</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Method</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Grant / Reservation</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Requirements</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Status Result</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Case</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Express</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Both</p></td><td><p>Deed (s 52 LPA); s 1 LP(MP)A 1989; registration s 27(2)(d) LRA 2002</p></td><td><p>Legal (if registered); Equitable if not</p></td><td><p>\u2014</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Necessity</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Both (reservation very rare)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Easement essential \u2014 landlocked land only; not merely advantageous</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Same status as the document</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Pryce v McGuinness [1966]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Common intention</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Both (heavy burden for reservation)</p></td><td><p>Specific intended purpose; easement necessary to achieve it</p></td><td><p>Same status as the document</p></td><td><p>Wong v Beaumont [1965]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Wheeldon v Burrows</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Grant only</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Quasi-easement; continuous &amp; apparent; necessary for reasonable enjoyment; in use at date of transfer</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Same status as document</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Wheeler v JJ Saunders [1995]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>s 62 LPA 1925</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Grant only</p></td><td><p>Conveyance (deed only); prior diversity of occupation OR continuous &amp; apparent</p></td><td><p>Legal (operates on deeds)</p></td><td><p>Wright v Macadam [1949]; P&amp;S Platt v Crouch [2003]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Prescription</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Grant only (long use)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>20+ years; nec vi, nec clam, nec precario; freeholder vs freeholder; continuous user</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Legal</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Mills v Silver [1991]</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 6 \u2014 Wheeldon v Burrows vs s 62 LPA 1925: Key Distinctions</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Feature</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Wheeldon v Burrows</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>s 62 LPA 1925</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Applies to</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Grant only (not reservation)</p></td><td><p>Grant only (not reservation)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Document type</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Any transfer, lease or contract</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Conveyance (deed) only \u2014 NOT a contract</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Prior use required</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Quasi-easement by common owner</p></td><td><p>Prior diversity of occupation (licence/permission) OR continuous &amp; apparent (P&amp;S Platt)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Continuous &amp; apparent</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Always required</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Required where no diversity of occupation</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Necessary for reasonable use</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Required</p></td><td><p>Not required</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Effect</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Implies quasi-easement into document</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Upgrades informal licence/permission into full legal easement</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Key case</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Wheeler v JJ Saunders [1995]</p></td><td><p>Wright v Macadam [1949]; P&amp;S Platt v Crouch [2003]</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 7 \u2014 Prescription: Three Methods</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Method</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Rule</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Weakness / Note</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Common law</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Use since time immemorial (1189); rebuttable if shown to have been impossible at any point in history</p></td><td><p>Very rarely succeeds in practice</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Lost Modern Grant</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Court fictionally presumes a grant was made but lost; 20 years&#x27; use raises presumption</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Servient owner may rebut \u2014 but cannot rebut merely by showing no grant was made</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Prescription Act 1832</strong></span></p></td><td><p>20 yrs (general rights) / 40 yrs (right to light); right becomes absolute after 40 yrs / 20 yrs (light)</p></td><td><p>Most commonly used in practice</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>All methods: nec vi</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No force; no ignoring signs/protests</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Winterburn v Bennett [2017] \u2014 sign re-erected \u2192 use by force \u2192 no easement</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>All methods: nec clam</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Not secret; reasonable opportunity for servient owner to discover use</p></td><td><p>\u2014</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>All methods: nec </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>precario</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Not by permission; toleration \u2260 permission</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Mills v Silver [1991]</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 8 \u2014 Enforceability against New Servient Owner</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Type of Easement</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Registered Land</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Unregistered Land</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Express legal</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Must be substantively registered (s 27(2)(d) LRA 2002) \u2014 then always binding</p></td><td><p>Binds world (legal interests bind the world); overrides on first registration (Sch 1 para 3 LRA 2002)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Implied legal</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Overriding interest (Sch 3 para 3 LRA 2002) if: known to new owner; OR obvious on careful inspection; OR exercised within 1 yr before transfer</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Binds world; overriding on first registration</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Express equitable</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Protect by notice on charges register (s 32 LRA 2002); if unprotected, not binding on purchaser for value (s 29(1)); volunteer always bound (s 28)</p></td><td><p>Register Class D(iii) Land Charge (LCA 1972 s 2(5)(iii)); if unregistered, void against purchaser for money&#x27;s worth of legal estate (s 4(6)); volunteer always bound</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Implied equitable</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Same rules as express equitable easement</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Same rules as express equitable easement</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 9 \u2014 Leading Cases </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>at a Glance</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Case</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Topic</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Principle</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Re Ellenborough Park [1956]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Capability</p></td><td><p>Four-part test for characteristics of an easement; recreational use can be an easement</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Hill v Tupper [1863]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Accommodation</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Right benefiting business only (not land) cannot accommodate dominant tenement</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Moody v </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Steggles</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> [1879]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Accommodation</p></td><td><p>Nexus between land and business \u2192 right benefiting business also benefits land</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Pugh v Savage [1970]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Proximity</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Tenements need not adjoin; sufficient proximity required</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Batchelor v Marlow [2003]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Exclusive possession</p></td><td><p>Ouster principle: no reasonable use remaining for servient owner \u2192 disqualified</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Moncrieff v Jamieson [2007]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Exclusive possession</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Scottish persuasive: test is whether servient owner retains possession &amp; control</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Kettel v </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Bloomfold</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> [2012]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Exclusive possession</p></td><td><p>Applied ouster test in Moncrieff way: parking easement valid; servient owner retained control</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Green v Ashco [1966]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Permission</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Moving van on request = acknowledgement of permission not right; no easement</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Rance v Elvin [1985]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Expenditure</p></td><td><p>Water supply easement upheld; quasi-contractual obligation on dominant owner to pay share of bills</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Mills v Silver [1991]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Prescription</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>&quot;Reasonably regular&quot; use without force, secrecy or permission sufficient for prescription</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Winterburn v Bennett [2017]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Prescription</p></td><td><p>Ignoring repeatedly re-erected signs = use by force \u2192 no easement by prescription</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Cordell v Second </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Clanfield</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> [1969]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Reservation</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Reservations strictly construed against reserving party per transfer deed</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Wong v Beaumont [1965]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Common intention</p></td><td><p>Ventilation duct implied \u2014 necessary for known specific purpose (restaurant use)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Wheeler v JJ Saunders [1995]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Wheeldon v Burrows</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Second means of access equally convenient \u2192 easement not necessary for reasonable enjoyment</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Wright v Macadam [1949]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>s 62 LPA 1925</p></td><td><p>Permissive use of shed upgraded to legal easement by s 62 on grant of new lease</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>P&amp;S Platt v Crouch [2003]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>s 62 LPA 1925</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Prior diversity of occupation not required where right is continuous &amp; apparent</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Pryce v McGuinness [1966]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Necessity</p></td><td><p>Drainage etc highly advantageous but not essential; only landlocked land qualifies</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Donovan v Rana [2014]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Common intention</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Planning permission for dwelling = sufficient evidence of common intention to imply services easement</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Yeung v Patel [2014]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Common intention reservation</p></td><td><p>Heavy burden for reservation by common intention; having exercised right openly insufficient</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>3. Flashcard Q&amp;A Pairs</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Question</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Answer</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is an easement?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>A proprietary right to use land belonging to someone else.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What are the two types of </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>easement</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> by legal status?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Legal (LPA s 1(2)(a) \u2014 freehold/leasehold duration; registered) and Equitable (s 1(3) \u2014 all others).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What are the four Re Ellenborough Park requirements?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>(i) Dominant &amp; servient tenement; (ii) accommodates dominant tenement; (iii) no common ownership; (iv) lies in grant.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>How does Hill v Tupper differ from Moody v </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Steggles</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Hill v Tupper: right only benefited the business, not the land \u2014 not an easement. Moody v Steggles: nexus between land and business \u2014 right benefiting business also benefits land.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is the ouster principle?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>From Batchelor v Marlow: a right cannot be an easement if it leaves the servient owner with no reasonable use of the land.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is the possession &amp; control test?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>From Moncrieff v Jamieson (persuasive, Scottish): disqualified only if servient owner loses ultimate possession and control; sole use for limited purpose is not inconsistent.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What does nec vi, nec clam, nec </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>precario</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> mean?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Without force; without secrecy; without permission \u2014 the three requirements for use &quot;as of right&quot; in prescription.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is the only right implied by necessity?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>A right of way to otherwise landlocked land (Pryce v McGuinness [1966]).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What must be shown for common intention implied easement?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Specific intended use of the land; easement necessary to achieve that specific purpose (not merely a general intention: Pwllbach Colliery v Woodman).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What are the Wheeldon v Burrows requirements?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Grant only; quasi-easement by common owner; continuous &amp; apparent; necessary for reasonable enjoyment; in use at date of transfer.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is the key distinction between Wheeldon v Burrows and s 62?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>W v B applies to any document (including contracts); s 62 applies only to conveyances (deeds). s 62 requires prior diversity of occupation OR continuous &amp; apparent (P&amp;S Platt). W v B requires reasonable necessity; s 62 does not.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What does s 62 LPA 1925 &quot;upgrade&quot; mean?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>An informal permission or licence existing before the grant is upgraded into a full legal easement when a conveyance is executed.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>How is an express legal easement protected in registered land?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Substantive registration at Land Registry (s 27(2)(d) LRA 2002) \u2014 benefit noted on Property Register; burden on Charges Register.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>How is an implied legal easement enforced in registered land?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Overriding interest under Sch 3 para 3 LRA 2002 if: within new owner&#x27;s knowledge; OR obvious on careful inspection; OR exercised within 1 year before transfer.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>How is an equitable easement protected in registered land?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Notice on the Charges Register of the servient title (s 32 LRA 2002); if unprotected, void against purchaser for value (s 29(1) LRA 2002).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>How is an equitable easement protected in unregistered land?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Class D(iii) Land Charge (LCA 1972 s 2(5)(iii)); if unregistered, void against purchaser for money or money&#x27;s worth of legal estate (s 4(6)).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>When does a reservation receive strict construction?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Always: strictly construed against the reserving party per the transfer deed (Cordell v Second Clanfield [1969]).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Does a new type of right prevent it being an easement?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No \u2014 the list is not exhaustive (Dyce v Lady James Hay [1852]), but a new easement must not be purely negative in character (Phipps v Pears [1965]).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What remedies are available for interference with an easement?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Prohibitory injunction; damages (in lieu or addition); mandatory injunction to remove obstruction.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Can an easement exist &quot;in gross&quot;?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No \u2014 it must benefit a dominant tenement; it cannot be held independently of land (Hawkins v Rutter [1892]).</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>4. Common Exam Pitfalls &amp; Tricky Distinctions</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Pitfall / Distinction</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Explanation</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Easement vs licence confusion</strong></span></p></td><td><p>A licence is personal and cannot bind third parties. An easement is proprietary. Do not conclude an easement exists simply because someone has permission to use land \u2014 Green v Ashco: permission given each time \u2192 licence only.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Accommodation test \u2014 Hill v Tupper trap</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>A right that only benefits a business carried on at the dominant land does NOT accommodate the tenement unless there is a nexus between the land and the business (Moody v Steggles). Always ask: does the right benefit the land itself, not just the owner personally?</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Necessity vs common intention \u2014 not interchangeable</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Necessity is confined strictly to landlocked land. Do not stretch it to drainage, electricity etc (Pryce v McGuinness). Use common intention (Wong v Beaumont) for specific purposes that go beyond landlocked access.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Wheeldon v Burrows only applies to grants</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>W v B cannot imply a reservation. A seller/landlord claiming a right over land they have sold/leased must use necessity or common intention (and faces a heavy burden).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>s 62 requires a deed, not a contract</strong></span></p></td><td><p>S 62 only operates on a conveyance (deed). A contract for sale does NOT trigger the upgrade effect. Also: prior diversity of occupation is NOT always required after P&amp;S Platt v Crouch [2003] \u2014 if the right is continuous and apparent, s 62 can apply without it.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Ouster test \u2014 which case applies?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Batchelor v Marlow (ouster/no reasonable use) is binding English law. Moncrieff v Jamieson (possession &amp; control) is persuasive Scottish law. English courts (Kettel v Bloomfold) have applied the ouster test in a Moncrieff way \u2014 applying both in effect. Do not apply only Moncrieff.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Prescription \u2014 &quot;as of right&quot; vs toleration</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Toleration of use by the servient owner does NOT amount to permission. The servient owner must actively grant permission for use to be precario. Mills v Silver: use with the landowner&#x27;s knowledge but without express permission = valid.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Prescription \u2014 ignoring signs = force</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Winterburn v Bennett: repeatedly ignoring a sign saying land is private = use by force (vi) \u2192 no easement by prescription. Signs are critical.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Equitable easements in registered land \u2014 protection</strong></span></p></td><td><p>An equitable easement that is not protected by notice on the charges register is void against a purchaser for valuable consideration (s 29(1) LRA 2002). A donee/volunteer is always bound (s 28). Do not confuse with implied legal easements which can be overriding (Sch 3 para 3).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Reservation \u2014 strictly construed</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Cordell v Second Clanfield: any ambiguity in a reservation is resolved against the reserving party. Do not imply a wider reservation than the words of the deed allow.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>A term certain easement cannot be &quot;inherently equitable&quot;</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Only easements for an uncertain term are inherently equitable (e.g. &quot;until the car park is built&quot;). A term certain easement (freehold or fixed term lease) can be legal \u2014 it is only equitable if legal formalities fail.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Benefit always passes with dominant land</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Regardless of whether the easement is legal or equitable, the benefit passes automatically on transfer of the dominant land (s 205(ix) LPA 1925; s 62(1) LPA 1925). The enforceability question is about the burden against the new servient owner.</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>"}], "Freehold Covenants": [{"id": "covenants-notes", "title": "W5: Freehold Covenants", "content": "<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>FREEHOLD COVENANTS \u2014 COMPREHENSIVE REVISION NOTES</strong></span></p>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>1. Structured Topic Overview</strong></span></h3>\n<p>Freehold covenants analysis follows a strict logical sequence:</p>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>STAGE 1 \u2014 IDENTIFY THE COVENANT</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>Positive: promise to do something \u2014 not a proprietary right; &quot;hand in pocket&quot; test</li><li>Negative/restrictive: promise not to do something \u2014 equitable interest in land; recognised proprietary right</li><li>Mixed covenant: split into separate positive and negative covenants if possible; if not, characterise the substance as one overall obligation with a condition attached</li></ul>\n<p>Formalities: valid restrictive covenant must be in writing, signed by grantor (LPA 1925 s 53(1)(a))</p>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>STAGE 2 \u2014 IS IT BETWEEN THE ORIGINAL PARTIES?</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>If so: fully enforceable in contract between covenantor and covenantee \u2014 no issue</li><li>Legal issue only arises on succession (sale of dominant or servient land)</li></ul>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>STAGE 3 \u2014 HAS THE BURDEN PASSED? (to enforce against successor covenantor)</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>Common law: burden NEVER passes (Austerberry v Oldham; Rhone v Stephens)</li><li>Equity (Tulk v Moxhay): burden passes IF \u2014 (i) covenant is restrictive; (ii) accommodates dominant tenement; (iii) intention to run; (iv) notice (registered: notice on charges register s 32 LRA; unregistered: Class D(II) Land Charge)</li><li>Indirect enforcement (positive covenants): continuing liability of original covenantor (s 79 LPA); indemnity covenant chain; Halsall v Brizell mutual benefit &amp; burden</li></ul>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>STAGE 4 \u2014 HAS THE BENEFIT PASSED? (to enforce by successor covenantee)</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>Must use SAME set of rules as burden (cannot mix equity and common law)</li><li>Equity: benefit must touch and concern land + pass by annexation (express or statutory s 78 LPA), assignment (s 53(1)(c) LPA), or building scheme (Ellison v Reacher)</li><li>Common law: implied assignment (P&amp;A Swift: touch &amp; concern + intention to run + covenantee/successor holds legal estate)</li></ul>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>STAGE 5 \u2014 REMEDIES AND DISCHARGE</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>Remedies: injunction (prohibitory or mandatory); equitable damages in lieu (Wrotham Park \u2014 percentage of developer profits)</li><li>Discharge: merger (Re Tiltwood); express release by deed; implied release (acquiescence); s 84(1) LPA 1925 (Upper Tribunal \u2014 grounds: obsolete; impedes reasonable use; agreement; no injury)</li></ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>2. Summary Revision Tables</strong></span></h3>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 1 \u2014 Key Definitions</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Term</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Definition</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Source</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Covenant</strong></span></p></td><td><p>A promise, usually contained in a deed; a deed is not essential</p></td><td><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Covenantee</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Receives the benefit; can sue on breach; holds dominant land</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Covenantor</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Makes the promise; can be sued on breach; holds servient land</p></td><td><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Dominant land</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Land benefitted by the covenant</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Servient land</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Land burdened by the covenant</p></td><td><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Positive covenant</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Promise to do something; &quot;hand in pocket&quot; test; not a proprietary right; burden does not pass at common law or equity</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Haywood v Brunswick PBBS [1881]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Restrictive covenant</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Promise not to do something; equitable interest; burden can pass in equity (Tulk v Moxhay)</p></td><td><p>Rhone v Stephens [1994]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Successor covenantee</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>New owner of the dominant land</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Successor covenantor</strong></span></p></td><td><p>New owner of the servient land</p></td><td><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Annexation</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Benefit becomes permanently part of dominant land \u2014 passes automatically on sale without mention in transfer deed</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Rogers v Hosegood [1900]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Building scheme</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Set of mutually enforceable covenants over a defined estate; treated as by-laws enforceable by/against all owners</p></td><td><p>Ellison v Reacher [1908]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Indemnity covenant</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Primary obligation by successor to compensate original covenantor for losses caused by successor&#x27;s breach</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>General law</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 2 \u2014 Positive vs Restrictive Covenants</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Feature</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Positive Covenant</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Restrictive Covenant</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Definition</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Promise to do something</p></td><td><p>Promise not to do something</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Test</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>&quot;Hand in pocket&quot; test: requires expenditure of money, effort or time</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Substance is prohibitory \u2014 look at the essence of the obligation</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Proprietary right?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>No \u2014 not a recognised proprietary interest</p></td><td><p>Yes \u2014 equitable interest in land</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Burden passes at common law?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No (Austerberry; Rhone v Stephens)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No \u2014 but equity intervenes</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Burden passes in equity?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>No \u2014 equity will not enforce positive covenants against successors (Haywood v Brunswick)</p></td><td><p>Yes \u2014 if Tulk v Moxhay conditions met</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Enforcement against successor</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Indirect only: original covenantor liability (s 79 LPA); indemnity chain; Halsall v Brizell; long lease</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Direct if Tulk v Moxhay conditions met + benefit passed</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 3 \u2014 Tulk v </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Moxhay</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> [1848]: Equitable Burden Test</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Requirement</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule / Detail</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Authority</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>1. Covenant must be restrictive</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Substance must be prohibitory; positive covenants cannot bind successors in equity</p></td><td><p>Rhone v Stephens [1994]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>2. Must accommodate dominant tenement</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Covenantee must hold dominant land at creation and enforcement; covenant must touch and concern the land (affect nature, quality, use or value); dominant and servient must be sufficiently proximate</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>LCC v Allen [1914]; P&amp;A Swift [1989]; Bailey v Stephens [1862]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>3. Intention for burden to run</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Express wording OR implied by s 79 LPA 1925 (deemed made by covenantor on behalf of successors unless contrary intention expressed)</p></td><td><p>LPA 1925 s 79</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>4. Notice \u2014 Registered land</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Notice on charges register of servient title (LRA 2002 s 32); unprotected covenant void against purchaser for value</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>LRA 2002 s 32</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>4. Notice \u2014 Unregistered land</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Class D(II) Land Charge (LCA 1972); unprotected covenant void against purchaser for value regardless of actual knowledge</p></td><td><p>LCA 1972</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 4 \u2014 Passing the Benefit in Equity (</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Renals</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> v Cowlishaw Methods)</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Method</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule / Detail</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Authority</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Express annexation</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Words of covenant make clear benefit is intended to attach to dominant land (not merely to person of covenantee); &quot;for the benefit of [named land] and its successors in title&quot;</p></td><td><p>Rogers v Hosegood [1900]; Renals v Cowlishaw [1878]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Statutory annexation (s 78 LPA 1925)</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>A covenant relating to land is deemed to be made with the covenantee and successors in title to the land intended to benefit; annexation is automatic unless excluded expressly or impliedly by alternative provision</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Federated Homes v Mill Lodge [1980]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Assignment</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Benefit not annexed at outset; must be expressly assigned each time land is transferred; must comply with s 53(1)(c) LPA (in writing, signed by person transferring benefit); treated as separate interest</p></td><td><p>LPA 1925 s 53(1)(c)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Building scheme</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>All buyers from same seller; estate divided into plots; covenants intended to benefit all plots; each buyer knows covenants benefit all plots. Enforced as mutual set of by-laws \u2014 no need to specifically trace benefit</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Ellison v Reacher [1908]</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 5 \u2014 Common Law: Benefit (Implied Assignment \u2014 P&amp;A Swift Test)</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Requirement</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Covenant must touch and concern the land</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Benefits dominant land itself: affects nature, quality, use or value; not personal; only benefits dominant owner for the time being; ceases to benefit if severed from land</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Intention that </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>benefit</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> runs</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Express or implied (s 78 LPA 1925)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Legal estate at creation and enforcement</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Original covenantee must have held a legal estate when covenant was made; successor must hold legal estate at time of enforcement; estates need not be of same nature (Smith and Snipes Hall Farm Ltd v River Douglas [1949])</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 6 \u2014 Indirect Enforcement of Positive Covenants</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Method</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>How It Works</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Limitation</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Continuing liability of original covenantor (s 79 LPA)</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Original covenantor liable for own AND successors&#x27; breaches; remedy = damages only (no longer in possession)</p></td><td><p>Damages only; cannot compel performance</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Indemnity covenant chain</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Each sale of burdened land requires successor to enter IC promising to comply and indemnify; creates chain back to original covenantor; original covenantor can sue direct successor only</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Chain fails if any link in chain dies or becomes bankrupt</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Halsall v </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Brizell</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> / Mutual benefit &amp; burden</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Burden passes where: (i) clear link between burden and benefit; (ii) genuine choice to take or reject benefit; (iii) benefit and burden conferred in same transaction</p></td><td><p>Rhone v Stephens: no general principle; Thamesmead v Allotey: must be genuine choice</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Long lease</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Dispose of land by long lease instead of freehold sale; all covenants (except personal) enforceable by/against successors via privity of estate</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Not always commercially appropriate</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 7 \u2014 Discharge and Modification of Restrictive Covenants</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Method</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Authority / Note</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Merger</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Covenant discharged when same person becomes owner of both dominant and servient land</p></td><td><p>Re Tiltwood, Sussex [1978]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Express release</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Dominant owner agrees to discharge covenant, usually for payment; must be by deed</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Implied release</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Dominant owner does nothing when covenant is openly being breached over time \u2014 acquiescence</p></td><td><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>s 84(1)(a) LPA 1925</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Upper Tribunal: obsolete due to changes in character of property or neighbourhood</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Only applies to restrictive covenants</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>s 84(</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>1)(</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>aa) LPA 1925</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Continued existence impedes reasonable use for public or private purposes; covenant confers no practical value or contrary to public interest; financial compensation must be adequate</p></td><td><p>Upper Tribunal discretion</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>s 84(1)(b) LPA 1925</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Dominant owners expressly or impliedly agree to discharge</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Upper Tribunal</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>s 84(1)(c) LPA 1925</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Dominant owners will not suffer injury; tribunal can override frivolous objections; must have regard to social/economic concerns</p></td><td><p>Upper Tribunal</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 8 \u2014 Leading Cases </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>at a Glance</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Case</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Topic</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Core Principle</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Haywood v Brunswick PBBS [1881]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Positive covenants</p></td><td><p>&quot;Hand in pocket&quot; test; positive covenants will not be enforced against successor covenantors in equity</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Austerberry v Oldham Corp [1885]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Burden at common law</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Burden of a covenant does not pass at common law; confirmed in Rhone v Stephens</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Rhone v Stephens [1994]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Burden; positive v restrictive</p></td><td><p>No general principle burden passes at common law; substance of covenant must be restrictive to be enforced in equity</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Tulk v </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Moxhay</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> [1848]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Equitable burden</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Equitable exception: restrictive covenant passes in equity if four conditions met</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>LCC v Allen [1914]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Accommodation</p></td><td><p>Covenantee and successors must retain interest in dominant land at creation and enforcement</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>P&amp;A Swift Investments v CES [1989]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Touch and concern</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Covenant must benefit dominant owner only whilst owning dominant land; affect nature/quality/use/value; not personal</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Bailey v Stephens [1862]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Proximity</p></td><td><p>Dominant and servient land must be in sufficient proximity (need not share boundary)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Rogers v </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Hosegood</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> [1900]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Express annexation</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Covenant &quot;for benefit of owners and successors in title&quot; to named land = express annexation</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Renals</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> v Cowlishaw [1878]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Express annexation</p></td><td><p>Covenant stated for benefit of &quot;heirs, executors and assignees&quot; (people not land) = not annexed</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Federated Homes v Mill Lodge [1980]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Statutory annexation</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>S 78 LPA 1925 makes annexation automatic unless excluded</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Ellison v Reacher [1908]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Building scheme</p></td><td><p>Conditions for a valid building scheme; treated as guidelines not strict requirements; mutual enforceability</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Halsall v </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Brizell</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> [1957]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Mutual benefit &amp; burden</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Positive covenant burden passes where clear link between burden and benefit, genuine choice, same transaction</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Rhone v Stephens [1994]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Mutual benefit &amp; burden</p></td><td><p>No general principle of benefit = burden; conditions must be strictly met</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Thamesmead Town v Allotey [1998]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Mutual benefit &amp; burden</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No genuine choice to reject benefit = normal rule applies; burden does not pass</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Davies v Jones [2009]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Mutual benefit &amp; burden</p></td><td><p>Benefit and burden must be conferred in the same transaction</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Wrotham Park Estate v Parkside Homes [1974]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Remedies</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Mandatory injunction refused (waste of houses); equitable damages awarded as % of developer&#x27;s profits</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Re </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Tiltwood</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>, Sussex [1978]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Discharge</p></td><td><p>Covenant discharged by merger when dominant and servient land come under common ownership</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>3. Flashcard Q&amp;A Pairs</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Question</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Answer</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is the &quot;hand in pocket&quot; test?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>If the covenantor must spend money, effort or time to comply, the covenant is positive. Look at the substance/essence of the obligation, not the form of words.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Does the burden of a covenant pass at common law?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No \u2014 never. Austerberry v Oldham Corporation [1885], confirmed in Rhone v Stephens [1994]. The covenant remains enforceable only against the original covenantor.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What are the four Tulk v </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Moxhay</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> conditions for equitable burden?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>(1) Covenant must be restrictive; (2) must accommodate dominant tenement (touch and concern + proximity); (3) intention to run (express or s 79 LPA); (4) notice (registered: notice on charges register; unregistered: Class D(II) Land Charge).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Can the burden of a positive covenant EVER pass to a successor?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Not directly. Indirect methods: (1) continuing liability of original covenantor (s 79 LPA); (2) chain of indemnity covenants; (3) Halsall v Brizell mutual benefit &amp; burden (three conditions); (4) grant of long lease instead of freehold.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What are the three </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Renals</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> v Cowlishaw methods for passing the benefit in equity?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Annexation (express or statutory s 78 LPA); Assignment (s 53(1)(c) LPA \u2014 in writing, signed); Building scheme (Ellison v Reacher conditions).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What did Federated Homes v Mill Lodge Properties [1980] establish?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>S 78 LPA 1925 makes annexation of benefit automatic \u2014 unless expressly excluded or an alternative method for passing the benefit is provided in the transfer deed.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is the effect of s 79 LPA 1925?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Implied intention that the burden of a covenant runs with the land \u2014 covenant is deemed made by the covenantor on behalf of successors in title, unless a contrary intention is expressed.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What distinguishes Rogers v </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Hosegood</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> from </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Renals</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> v Cowlishaw on express annexation?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Rogers: covenant for benefit of &quot;owners and successors in title&quot; to named land = annexed to the land. Renals: covenant for benefit of &quot;heirs, executors and assignees&quot; (people not land) = not annexed.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What are the Ellison v Reacher building scheme conditions?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>All buyers buy from same seller; seller divided estate into plots; covenants intended to benefit all plots; each buyer knows this. Treated as guidelines \u2014 court must be satisfied of mutual intention to create enforceable obligations.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What are the three Halsall v </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Brizell</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> conditions for mutual benefit and burden?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>(1) Clear link between the specific burden and the specific benefit; (2) genuine choice whether to take the benefit; (3) benefit and burden conferred in the same transaction.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What remedies are available for breach of a restrictive covenant?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Prohibitory injunction (prevent ongoing/threatened breach); mandatory injunction (remedy completed breach); equitable damages in lieu of injunction (Wrotham Park: % of developer&#x27;s profits if mandatory injunction would be oppressive).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What happened in Wrotham Park and why is it significant?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Mandatory injunction refused to demolish houses built in breach of restrictive covenant (&quot;unpardonable waste of much needed houses&quot;). Equitable damages awarded as a percentage of developer profits \u2014 what dominant owner could have charged for release.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>are</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> the s 84(1) LPA 1925 grounds for Upper Tribunal discharge/modification?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>(a) Obsolete due to change in character; (aa) impedes reasonable use, no practical benefit or contrary to public interest, financial compensation adequate; (b) agreement (express or implied); (c) no injury to dominant owner. Only applies to restrictive covenants.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>How is a restrictive covenant protected in registered land?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Entry of a notice on the charges register of the servient title (LRA 2002 s 32). If unprotected, the covenant is not binding on a purchaser for value (though a volunteer/donee is always bound).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>How is a restrictive covenant protected in unregistered land?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Entry of a Class D(II) Land Charge (LCA 1972). If unprotected, void against a purchaser for value regardless of actual knowledge (Midland Bank v Green principle applies by analogy).</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>4. Common Exam Pitfalls &amp; Tricky Distinctions</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Pitfall / Distinction</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Explanation</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Cannot mix equitable and common law rules</strong></span></p></td><td><p>To enforce a covenant, you must use either the equitable rules OR the common law rules throughout \u2014 you cannot mix them. If burden has passed in equity (Tulk v Moxhay), the benefit must also have passed in equity (annexation/assignment/building scheme). Never apply a common law benefit rule to an equitable burden case.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Positive covenants: burden NEVER passes directly</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No matter how the covenant is worded, the burden of a positive covenant cannot be made to pass to a successor covenantor either at common law or in equity (Rhone v Stephens). The only remedies are indirect: original covenantor liability, indemnity chain, or Halsall v Brizell. Never say a positive covenant binds a successor directly.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Halsall v </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Brizell</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>: three conditions are strict</strong></span></p></td><td><p>The mutual benefit and burden doctrine is not a general principle (Rhone v Stephens). All three conditions must be met: (1) clear link; (2) genuine choice (Thamesmead v Allotey: if there is no real choice but to take the benefit, the rule does not apply); (3) same transaction (Davies v Jones). Test each condition carefully.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>S 78 annexation is automatic \u2014 but can be excluded</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Federated Homes makes s 78 LPA 1925 operate automatically for all covenants relating to land, unless: (i) the covenant expressly excludes it; or (ii) an alternative method of passing the benefit (such as assignment) is provided in the deed. Look for exclusion language before assuming automatic annexation applies.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Renals</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> v Cowlishaw: benefit to persons \u2260 benefit to land</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Express annexation requires the benefit to be expressed as attaching to the land, not just to the people of the covenantee. &quot;For the benefit of the named land and its successors in title&quot; = annexed. &quot;For the benefit of the covenantee, their heirs, executors and assignees&quot; = NOT annexed (Renals v Cowlishaw \u2014 people, not land).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Assignment must occur every transfer \u2014 it does not run automatically</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Unlike annexation (which permanently attaches to the land), assignment of the benefit must take place expressly each time the dominant land is sold. If even one transfer occurs without assignment, the chain is broken and the benefit is lost to all subsequent owners. This is a key distinction from annexation.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Touch and concern: personal covenants do not pass</strong></span></p></td><td><p>A covenant that is &quot;expressed to be personal&quot; or that only benefits the covenantee in a personal capacity (not as landowner) does not touch and concern the land and cannot pass to successors. P&amp;A Swift: must benefit the dominant owner only whilst they own the land, and affect the nature/quality/use/value of the land.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Wrotham Park damages: based on profits, not loss</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Equitable damages in lieu of a mandatory injunction for a covenant breach are not calculated on the diminution in value of the dominant land (which may be nominal). They are based on a percentage of the profits made by the person in breach \u2014 what the dominant owner could reasonably have charged for release of the covenant.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>s 84(1) Upper Tribunal: only applies to restrictive covenants</strong></span></p></td><td><p>The power to discharge or modify under s 84(1) LPA 1925 applies ONLY to restrictive covenants \u2014 not to positive covenants. Positive covenants cannot be modified or discharged by the Upper Tribunal under this provision.</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>"}], "Enforcement of Interests": [{"id": "enforcement-notes", "title": "W6: Enforcement of Interests", "content": "<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>ENFORCEMENT OF INTERESTS \u2014 COMPREHENSIVE REVISION NOTES</strong></span></p>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>1. Structured Topic Overview</strong></span></h3>\n<p>Enforcement of third-party interests is split between registered and unregistered land, and between different categories of interest.</p>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>REGISTERED LAND \u2014 THREE CATEGORIES (LRA 2002)</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>Registrable dispositions (s 27): must be registered to take legal effect \u2014 freehold/leasehold transfers, new leases &gt;7 yrs, express easements, legal mortgages, rights of entry</li><li>Interests protected by entry: equitable interests protected by notice (s 32, charges register) or restriction (s 40, proprietorship register)</li><li>Overriding interests (Sch 3): bind purchaser even without registration \u2014 Sch 3 para 1 (legal leases \u22647 yrs); para 2 (actual occupation); para 3 (implied legal easements)</li></ul>\n<p>Basic rule (s 28): interests take priority in order created \u2014 applies to donees. Exception (s 29): registrable disposition for valuable consideration takes priority over all pre-existing rights except protected/overriding interests.</p>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>OVERREACHING (registered and unregistered)</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>Applies to trust interests only (LPA 1925 ss 2 and 27)</li><li>Purchase price paid to at least two trustees \u2192 equitable interest moves from land to money</li><li>Flegg: payment to two trustees overreaches even if beneficiaries in actual occupation</li><li>Boland: payment to only one trustee does NOT overreach \u2192 interest remains in land</li></ul>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>UNREGISTERED LAND</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>Pre-1926: legal rights bind world; equitable rights subject to doctrine of notice (bona fide purchaser for value of legal estate without notice = &quot;equity&#x27;s darling&quot;)</li><li>Post-1926: most equitable interests protected by Land Charge (LCA 1972); unprotected = void against purchaser for value regardless of actual knowledge (Midland Bank v Green)</li><li>Cannot be protected by Land Charge: trust interests (overreaching); equitable easements/RCs created pre-1926 (doctrine of notice still applies)</li><li>Land charges registered against name of estate owner at time of creation; incorrect name = nullity (Diligent Finance v Alleyne)</li><li>On sale, unregistered land must be registered for first time (LRA 2002 s 4)</li></ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>2. Summary Revision Tables</strong></span></h3>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 1 \u2014 Three Categories of Interest in Registered Land (LRA 2002)</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Category</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Examples</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Registrable dispositions (s 27)</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Must be registered to take legal effect (s 27(1)); &quot;compulsory registration&quot;</p></td><td><p>Transfer of freehold/leasehold (s 27(2)(a)); new lease &gt;7 yrs (s 27(2)(b)); express easement (s 27(2)(d)); legal mortgage (s 27(2)(f)); right of entry/forfeiture (s 27(2)(e))</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Protected by entry \u2014 Notice (s 32)</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Entry on charges register; does not guarantee validity \u2014 only binds purchaser if interest validly created; appropriate for interests intended to bind future owners</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Restrictive covenants (freehold); estate contracts; equitable easements; equitable leases; optional: legal leases 3\u20137 yrs</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Protected by entry \u2014 Restriction (s 40)</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Entry on proprietorship register; imposes conditions on registration of disposition; does not prevent disposition \u2014 only controls conditions</p></td><td><p>Trust of land interests; bankruptcy (trustee in bankruptcy&#x27;s consent required); overreaching trigger</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Overriding interests (Sch 3)</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Bind purchaser for value without any registration; retained in LRA 2002 in limited form</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Legal leases \u22647 yrs (Sch 3 para 1); actual occupation (Sch 3 para 2); implied legal easements (Sch 3 para 3)</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 2 \u2014 Priority Rules: s 28 vs s 29 LRA 2002</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>s 28 (Basic Rule)</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>s 29 (Exception)</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Applies to</strong></span></p></td><td><p>All interests; governs dispositions NOT for value (donee/gift/inheritance)</p></td><td><p>Registrable dispositions of registered estate for valuable consideration</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Effect</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Interests bind in order of creation \u2014 purchaser/donee takes subject to ALL pre-existing interests regardless of registration</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Takes free of all pre-existing interests EXCEPT: (i) registered/protected interests; (ii) overriding interests</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Volunteer</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Always bound by any pre-existing equitable interest regardless of protection status</p></td><td><p>N/A \u2014 s 29 only applies to purchasers for valuable consideration</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 3 \u2014 Overriding Interests: Schedule 3 LRA 2002</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Para</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Notes / Cases</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Para 1: Legal leases \u22647 yrs</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Binding on new freeholder without registration; rationale: too many to register; unreasonable to expect registration by short-term tenants</p></td><td><p>Equitable leases do NOT fall under para 1 (may fall under para 2)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Para 2: Actual occupation</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Equitable interest held by person in actual occupation at time of disposition (re: the land they occupy)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Link Lending v Bustard [2010]: multi-factor test \u2014 permanence; continuity; length/reason for absence; nature of property; personal circumstances</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Para 2 exception (b)</strong></span></p></td><td><p>No overriding interest if: inquiry was made of that person before disposition AND they failed to disclose when reasonably expected to do so</p></td><td><p>Protects purchasers from interests deliberately concealed</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Para 2 exception (c)</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No overriding interest if: occupation not obvious on reasonably careful inspection AND purchaser had no actual knowledge</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Both conditions (i) AND (ii) must be met for exception to apply</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Para 3: Implied legal easements</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Overriding if: (a) known to new owner; OR (b) obvious on reasonable inspection; OR (c) exercised within 12 months before disposition</p></td><td><p>Wheeldon v Burrows; common intention; necessity; s 62 LPA 1925 easements all capable of being overriding</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 4 \u2014 &quot;Actual Occupation&quot;: Key Cases (Sch 3 Para 2)</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Case</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Principle</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Williams &amp; Glyn&#x27;s Bank v Boland [1981]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>&quot;Actual occupation&quot; has its plain meaning \u2014 involves a degree of physical permanence; not a legalistic concept</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Abbey National v </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Cann</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> [1991]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Must be permanence and continuity \u2014 not a &quot;mere fleeting presence&quot; preparatory to moving in; presence of carpet layers and removal men insufficient</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Thompson v Foy [2010]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Person must be in actual occupation at the time of the transfer deed, and possibly also at registration, to claim overriding interest</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Chhokar v Chhokar [1984]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Actual occupation not defeated by temporary absences (holidays, hospital stays, business trips) \u2014 presence of belongings can be sufficient</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Stockholm Finance v Garden Holdings [1995]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Prolonged absence will defeat actual occupation \u2014 protracted periods of absence in a second home elsewhere goes beyond temporary absence</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Link Lending v Bustard [2010]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Multi-factor test: degree of permanence and continuity; intentions and wishes; length of absence; reason for absence; nature of property; personal circumstances</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 5 \u2014 Overreaching</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Issue</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule / Detail</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What it applies to</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Trust interests ONLY \u2014 the equitable beneficial interests of beneficiaries under a trust of land (LPA 1925 ss 2 and 27)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Applies to</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Both registered and unregistered land equally</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>How to overreach</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Capital money (purchase price/mortgage proceeds) must be paid to at least two trustees (or a trust corporation); money must NOT be paid directly to beneficiaries unless they are also trustees</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Effect of overreaching</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Equitable interest is transferred from the land to the money paid; purchaser takes land free of the trust interest; trustees must account to beneficiaries for their share of the proceeds</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>How a restriction triggers overreaching</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Restriction on proprietorship register sets condition: purchaser/lender must pay to two trustees; compliance = overreaching occurs</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>City of London BS v Flegg [1987]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Beneficiaries in actual occupation were overreached because mortgage monies were paid to two trustees (M-Bs); payment to two trustees sufficient even where beneficiaries in occupation and unaware of mortgage</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Williams &amp; Glyn&#x27;s Bank v Boland [1981]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Monies paid to only ONE trustee (husband sole legal owner); overreaching did NOT occur; wife&#x27;s interest remained in the land and was an overriding interest as she was in actual occupation</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 6 \u2014 Unregistered Land: Land Charges (LCA 1972)</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Class</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Interest Protected</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Effect of </strong><strong>Non-Registration</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Class C(I)</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Puisne mortgage (second legal mortgage)</p></td><td><p>Void against purchaser for value of legal estate</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Class C(IV)</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Estate contract (option, right of pre-emption, contract to convey)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Void against purchaser for money or money&#x27;s worth (Midland Bank v Green)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Class D(II)</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Restrictive covenant created after 1925</p></td><td><p>Void against purchaser for value of legal estate</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Class D(III)</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Equitable easement created after 1925</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Void against purchaser for value of legal estate</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Class F</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Spouse&#x27;s matrimonial right of occupation (Family Law Act 1996)</p></td><td><p>Void against purchaser for value</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>CANNOT be protected by Land Charge</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Trust interests (must be overreached); equitable easements and RCs created pre-1926 (doctrine of notice applies)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>\u2014</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 7 \u2014 Doctrine of Notice (Unregistered Land): &quot;Equity&#x27;s Darling&quot;</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Element</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule / Detail</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Cases</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Bona fide</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Acting in good faith; no fraudulent conduct</p></td><td><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Purchaser for value</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Pays consideration for the land; does not include donee/heir; nominal consideration counts (Midland Bank v Green)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Midland Bank Trust Co v Green [1981]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Legal estate</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Must acquire the legal estate (freehold or leasehold), not merely an equitable interest</p></td><td><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Without notice \u2014 Actual</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Purchaser has direct knowledge of the equitable interest</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>\u2014</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Without notice \u2014 Imputed</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Agent&#x27;s notice (actual or constructive) is imputed to the purchaser \u2014 e.g. solicitor&#x27;s knowledge</p></td><td><p>Kingsnorth Finance v Tizard [1986]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Without notice \u2014 Constructive</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Purchaser failed to make enquiries that ought reasonably to have been made; must inspect land and enquire of occupiers</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Hunt v Luck [1902]; Kingsnorth Finance v Tizard [1986]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Effect of being equity&#x27;s darling</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Takes land free of the equitable interest; interest is destroyed permanently \u2014 cannot revive against subsequent purchaser with notice</p></td><td><p>General law</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 8 \u2014 Key Cases </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>at a Glance</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Case</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Topic</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Core Principle</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>City of London BS v Flegg [1987]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Overreaching</p></td><td><p>Payment to two trustees overreaches beneficiaries&#x27; interests even where they are in actual occupation and unaware of the mortgage</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Williams &amp; Glyn&#x27;s Bank v Boland [1981]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Overreaching / actual occupation</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Payment to one trustee only = no overreaching; wife&#x27;s interest remained in land; overriding as she was in actual occupation</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Link Lending v Bustard [2010]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Actual occupation</p></td><td><p>Multi-factor test for actual occupation; courts reluctant to impose single test</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Abbey National v </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Cann</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> [1991]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Actual occupation</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>&quot;Mere fleeting presence&quot; preparatory to moving in insufficient for actual occupation</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Thompson v Foy [2010]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Actual occupation (timing)</p></td><td><p>Must be in actual occupation at date of transfer deed (and possibly registration)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Chhokar v Chhokar [1984]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Actual occupation</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Temporary absences (hospital, holiday, business trip) do not defeat actual occupation</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Stockholm Finance v Garden Holdings [1995]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Actual occupation</p></td><td><p>Prolonged absence (e.g. mainly living elsewhere) will defeat actual occupation</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Midland Bank Trust Co v Green [1981]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Land Charges / unregistered land</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Entry (or non-entry) of land charge is conclusive as to notice \u2014 knowledge of the interest is irrelevant; unregistered option void even where purchaser knew of it</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Diligent Finance Co v Alleyne [1972]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Land Charges \u2014 name requirement</p></td><td><p>Land charge registered against incorrect name (shortened name) is a nullity; must be against the full name as in the title deeds</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Hunt v Luck [1902]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Constructive notice</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Presence of tenant on land fixes purchaser with constructive notice of tenant&#x27;s leasehold interest</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Kingsnorth Finance v Tizard [1986]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Constructive / imputed notice</p></td><td><p>Surveyor&#x27;s failure to make further enquiries despite warning signs = constructive notice imputed to lender</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Mercer v Liverpool Railway [1903]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Legal rights in unregistered land</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>&quot;Legal rights bind the whole world&quot; \u2014 pre- and post-1926</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>3. Flashcard Q&amp;A Pairs</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Question</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Answer</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What are the three categories of interests in registered land under LRA 2002?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Registrable dispositions (s 27 \u2014 must register to take legal effect); interests protected by entry (notice s 32 or restriction s 40); overriding interests (Sch 3 \u2014 bind purchaser without registration).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is the basic rule of priority (s 28 LRA 2002)?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Interests take priority in order of creation. Applies to dispositions not for value (donees/gifts/inheritance). A donee is always bound by ALL pre-existing interests regardless of registration.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is the exception to the basic rule (s 29 LRA 2002)?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>A registrable disposition for valuable consideration takes priority over all pre-existing interests EXCEPT those which have been protected on the register (notice/restriction) or which are overriding interests.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What interests must be protected by notice (s 32 LRA 2002)?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Restrictive covenants affecting freehold land; estate contracts; equitable easements; equitable leases. Note: trust interests CANNOT be protected by notice (s 33) \u2014 use a restriction instead.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is a restriction (s 40 LRA 2002) and when is it used?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>An entry on the proprietorship register imposing conditions on registration of any disposition. Used for trust interests to trigger overreaching \u2014 requires payment to two trustees before any disposition is registered.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What are the three categories of overriding interest under Sch 3 LRA 2002?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Para 1: legal leases of 7 years or less. Para 2: interests of persons in actual occupation. Para 3: implied legal easements and profits \u00e0 prendre (if known/obvious/exercised within 12 months).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is the multi-factor test for actual occupation (Sch 3 para 2)?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Link Lending v Bustard [2010]: degree of permanence and continuity; intentions and wishes; length and reason for absence; nature of property; personal circumstances. Courts refuse to apply a single rigid test.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What are the two exceptions to Sch 3 para 2 overriding interests?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Para 2(b): inquiry was made and the person failed to disclose when reasonably expected to. Para 2(c)(i)+(ii): occupation not obvious on reasonably careful inspection AND purchaser had no actual knowledge (both must be met).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>How does overreaching work and what does it apply to?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Applies to trust interests ONLY (LPA 1925 ss 2 and 27). Capital money paid to at least two trustees \u2192 equitable interest moves from land to money. Works in both registered and unregistered land. Flegg: overreaching occurs even where beneficiaries in actual occupation.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Why did overreaching NOT occur in Boland?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Mortgage monies were paid to only one trustee (the husband as sole legal owner). Payment to fewer than two trustees does not overreach. Mrs Boland&#x27;s interest remained in the land and was overriding as she was in actual occupation.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What land charges protect which interests in unregistered land?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Class C(I): puisne mortgage. Class C(IV): estate contract/option. Class D(II): restrictive covenant post-1925. Class D(III): equitable easement post-1925. Class F: spouse&#x27;s right of occupation.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is the effect of failing to register a land charge?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>The interest is void against a purchaser for value of the land, regardless of the purchaser&#x27;s actual knowledge of the interest (Midland Bank v Green). The interest is NOT void against a donee/volunteer.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Who is &quot;equity&#x27;s darling&quot; and what are the five requirements?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>A bona fide purchaser for value of a legal estate without notice. All five elements must be satisfied: (1) bona fide; (2) purchaser; (3) for value; (4) legal estate; (5) without notice (actual, constructive or imputed).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What are the three types of notice in unregistered land?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Actual: direct knowledge. Constructive: would have known if proper enquiries made (inspect land; enquire of occupiers). Imputed: agent&#x27;s notice (actual or constructive) is attributed to the purchaser.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is the consequence of the equitable interest being defeated by equity&#x27;s darling?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>The interest is permanently destroyed \u2014 it cannot be revived so as to bind a subsequent purchaser who does have notice.</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>4. Common Exam Pitfalls &amp; Tricky Distinctions</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Pitfall / Distinction</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Explanation</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Trust interests CANNOT be protected by notice \u2014 use a restriction</strong></span></p></td><td><p>S 33 LRA 2002 expressly excludes beneficial interests under a trust of land from protection by notice. The correct mechanism is a restriction (s 40) on the proprietorship register, which triggers the overreaching requirement. A notice entered for a trust interest has no effect.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Overreaching and actual occupation: Flegg vs Boland</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>The key distinction is whether capital money was paid to two trustees. Flegg: two trustees (M-Bs) = overreaching occurred, even though Fleggs were in actual occupation. Boland: only one trustee = no overreaching, interest remained in land, and Mrs Boland&#x27;s actual occupation made it overriding. The number of trustees is the critical factor.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Land charge registration is absolute \u2014 actual knowledge is irrelevant</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Midland Bank v Green: a land charge not registered is void against a purchaser for value even if the purchaser actually knew of the interest. Conversely, a registered land charge binds a purchaser regardless of whether they searched. Never argue that actual knowledge cures non-registration or that ignorance defeats a registered charge.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Land charges are registered against the owner&#x27;s NAME \u2014 not the land</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Unlike registered land (where entries are against the title number), land charges are registered against the full name of the estate owner at the time of creation (s 3(1) LCA 1972). An incorrect name (even a shortened version) makes the registration a nullity (Diligent Finance v Alleyne). Always check the name against the title deeds.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Equitable interests pre-1926: doctrine of notice still applies</strong></span></p></td><td><p>The Land Charges Act 1972 system only applies to interests created AFTER 1925. Equitable easements and restrictive covenants created before 1926 cannot be protected as land charges \u2014 the old doctrine of notice still governs them. This is a frequently overlooked exception.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Actual occupation: timing matters for para 2</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Thompson v Foy: the person must be in actual occupation at the time of the disposition (execution of transfer deed) and potentially also at the time of registration. A person who moves out between exchange and completion may lose their overriding interest. Always check the chronology.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>A notice on the register does not guarantee the interest is valid</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Entry of a notice under s 32 LRA 2002 does not confirm that the interest has been properly created or is valid. It only means that IF the interest has been validly created, it will bind a subsequent purchaser. The validity of the underlying interest must be assessed separately.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Sch 3 para 2 exceptions: both conditions of (c) must be met</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Para 2(c) exception requires BOTH: (i) occupation not obvious on reasonably careful inspection AND (ii) purchaser had no actual knowledge. If either condition fails, the exception does not apply and the interest remains overriding. Do not apply the exception on the basis of one condition alone.</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>"}], "Co-ownership": [{"id": "co-ownership-notes", "title": "W7: Co-ownership", "content": "<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>CO-OWNERSHIP \u2014 COMPREHENSIVE REVISION NOTES</strong></span></p>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>1. Structured Topic Overview</strong></span></h3>\n<p>Co-ownership analysis follows a clear logical sequence in exam answers:</p>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>STAGE 1 \u2014 TRUST OF LAND</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>Concurrent co-ownership always imposes a trust of land (TOLATA 1996 s 1)</li><li>Legal title: held by trustees; equitable/beneficial title: held by beneficiaries</li><li>Express trust: evidenced in writing, signed by declarant(s) (LPA 1925 s 53(1)(b))</li><li>Implied trust: no formalities (s 53(2) LPA) \u2014 resulting trust (financial contribution); constructive trust (unconscionability)</li></ul>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>STAGE 2 \u2014 JOINT TENANCY OR TENANCY IN COMMON?</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>Legal title: ALWAYS joint tenancy (max 4 trustees, must be sui juris); cannot be severed (LPA 1925 s 36(2))</li><li>Equitable title: can be JT (four unities + no declaration of TiC) or TiC (any unity missing save possession; or express declaration; or presumption of TiC)</li><li>JT: right of survivorship; entire interest passes automatically on death \u2014 not affected by will or intestacy (Re Caines deceased [1978])</li><li>TiC: each has distinct but undivided share; survivorship does NOT apply; share passes under will or intestacy</li></ul>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>STAGE 3 \u2014 SEVERANCE (equitable JT \u2192 </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>TiC</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>)</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>Must occur in lifetime (will has no effect: Re Caines)</li><li>(a) Notice in writing (s 36(2) LPA): must show unequivocal and immediate intention to sever; served when delivered, not when read (Kinch v Bullard)</li><li>(b) Other acts or things (Williams v Hensman modes): unilateral act (total/partial/involuntary alienation); mutual agreement; mutual conduct</li></ul>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>STAGE 4 \u2014 DISPUTES: TOLATA 1996</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>S 14: anyone with interest may apply for order (sale; occupation; nature/extent of interest); court CANNOT order one beneficiary to buy out another</li><li>S 15: factors \u2014 (a) creators&#x27; intentions; (b) purpose of trust; (c) welfare of minors; (d) interests of secured creditors</li><li>Secured creditor interest (s 15(1)(d)) typically given greatest weight in practice (Bank of Ireland v Bell; Putnam v Taylor)</li><li>Court sale order = automatic overreaching event \u2014 trust interest moves to sale proceeds</li></ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>2. Summary Revision Tables</strong></span></h3>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 1 \u2014 Key Definitions</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Term</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Definition</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Source</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Co-ownership</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Two or more people own the same estate in the same piece of land at the same time; all entitled to possession of the whole (unity of possession)</p></td><td><p>TOLATA 1996</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Trust of land</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Imposed whenever land is co-owned; separates legal title (trustees) from equitable title (beneficiaries)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>TOLATA 1996 s 1</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Joint tenancy (JT)</strong></span></p></td><td><p>All co-owners form one single entity; own the whole collectively; right of survivorship applies; requires all four unities</p></td><td><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Tenancy in common (</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TiC</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>)</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Each co-owner has distinct but undivided share; only unity of possession required; no right of survivorship; share passes under will/intestacy</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Right of survivorship (ius </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>accrescendi</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>)</strong></span></p></td><td><p>On death of JT, their interest accrues automatically to surviving JTs; operates immediately on death; unaffected by will</p></td><td><p>Re Caines deceased [1978]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Sui juris</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Of full age (18+) and sound mind \u2014 legal title trustees must be sui juris</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>LPA 1925 ss 1(6) and 22</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Severance</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Converting an equitable JT interest into a TiC; does not end co-ownership; changes the basis on which equitable title is held; must occur in lifetime</p></td><td><p>LPA 1925 s 36(2)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Curtain principle</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Names of equitable owners do not appear on the register of title; nature of equitable holding is private</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Land Registration</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Aliquot share</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Equal share based on number of JTs at time of severance \u2014 not based on contributions (Goodman v Gallant [1986])</p></td><td><p>Goodman v Gallant [1986]</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 2 \u2014 Joint Tenancy vs Tenancy in Common</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Feature</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Joint Tenancy</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Tenancy in Common</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Unities required</strong></span></p></td><td><p>All four unities: possession, interest, time, title</p></td><td><p>Unity of possession only (others may exist)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Nature of holding</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>One single entity \u2014 own the whole collectively</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Distinct but undivided shares; e.g. 25% each</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Right of survivorship</strong></span></p></td><td><p>YES \u2014 ius accrescendi; unaffected by will</p></td><td><p>NO \u2014 share passes under will or intestacy</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Can be severed?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Yes \u2014 equitable JT only; legal JT cannot be severed (LPA s 36(2))</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>N/A \u2014 already TiC</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Legal title</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Must ALWAYS be held as JT (LPA s 36(2))</p></td><td><p>Legal title CANNOT be held as TiC</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Equitable title</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Can be JT or TiC \u2014 by express declaration or circumstance</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Can be equitable TiC if unities or declaration support it</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Presumption</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Default where four unities exist and no declaration or words of TiC</p></td><td><p>Presumed where: business asset (Lake v Craddock); unequal purchase price of non-domestic property (Bull v Bull)</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 3 \u2014 Four Unities of Title</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Unity</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Requirement</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Notes</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Possession</strong></span></p></td><td><p>All entitled to possession of the whole; no co-owner has exclusive use of any part; REQUIRED for all co-ownership</p></td><td><p>Absence of possession unity = separate ownership not co-ownership</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Interest</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Same nature and duration of interest for each co-owner</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Leases: same length, same obligations</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Time</strong></span></p></td><td><p>All interests vest at the same time (need not sign or occupy at same time)</p></td><td><p>AG Securities: staggered start dates = no unity of time</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Title</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>All interests derive from the same document, or separate documents that are identical and interdependent</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Antoniades: separate but identical interdependent documents = unity of title satisfied</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Effect if unity missing</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Missing interest/time/title \u2192 no JT; if unity of possession also missing \u2192 no co-ownership; can only be TiC if possession present</p></td><td><p>LPA s 36(2)</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 4 \u2014 Severance: Methods and Rules</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Method</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Cases</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Notice in writing (s 36(2) LPA)</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Must show unequivocal and irrevocable intention to sever immediately; served when delivered (not when read); can sever even if written for another purpose</p></td><td><p>Re Draper&#x27;s Conveyance [1969]: divorce petition seeking immediate sale = sufficient. Harris v Goddard [1983]: &quot;such order as may be just&quot; = not sufficient (future, not immediate)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Service of notice</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Must be served on ALL equitable JTs; can be personal or by post; if posted and not returned undelivered = deemed served (s 196(3)/(4) LPA)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Kinch v Bullard [1999]: notice served when delivered to home; destruction of letter had no effect</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Unilateral act \u2014 Total alienation</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Permanent disposal of equitable interest by sale or gift</p></td><td><p>Act itself severs; other JTs need not know or consent</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Unilateral act \u2014 Partial alienation</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Temporary disposal by mortgage or lease; interest returns unencumbered when paid off/expires</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>First National Security v Hegarty [1985]: forged mortgage = mortgage on husband&#x27;s equitable interest only; severs his share</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Unilateral act \u2014 Involuntary alienation</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Bankruptcy \u2014 declared by court against joint tenant&#x27;s will</p></td><td><p>Severs bankrupt&#x27;s equitable share</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Mutual agreement</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>All equitable JTs agree one person&#x27;s interest is separate; need not be a specifically enforceable contract; significance is evidence of common intention to sever</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Burgess v Rawnsley [1975]; Hunter v Babbage [1995]: draft agreement showing separate shares suffices</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Mutual conduct</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Course of dealing showing interests are mutually treated as separate; falls short of full agreement; difficult to prove</p></td><td><p>Davis v Smith [2011]; Dunbabin v Dunbabin [2022]: mirror wills inconsistent with survivorship = severance. Gore and Snell [1990]: negotiations alone insufficient</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Effect of severance</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Severing JT takes an equal aliquot share (1/n where n = number of JTs); other JTs continue as JTs with each other; only both affected if only two JTs</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Goodman v Gallant [1986]</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 5 \u2014 TOLATA 1996 s 15 Factors for Dispute Resolution</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Factor</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule / Application</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Cases</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>s 15(1)(a): Creators&#x27; intentions</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Only applies to expressly created lifetime or will trusts; does NOT apply to everyday co-ownership situations</p></td><td><p>\u2014</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>s 15(1)(b): Purpose of trust</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Court assesses original purpose and whether it is continuing; if still being fulfilled \u2192 weighs AGAINST sale</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Re Evers&#x27; Trust [1980]: family home still usable = refused sale. Jones v Challenger [1961]: wife moved out, joint purpose ended = sale ordered</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>s 15(1)(c): Welfare of minors</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Continuity of living arrangements for minors is a priority; more weight to younger children; less weight to older minors (e.g. 17 yr old)</p></td><td><p>Fred Perry v Genis [2015]: children&#x27;s education disrupted but sale still ordered</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>s 15(1)(d): Secured creditor interests</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Treated with greater weight than other factors in practice; no presumption for or against sale (Mortgage Corp v Shaire [2001]); recent cases favour creditor strongly</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Bank of Ireland v Bell [2001]; Putnam v Taylor [2009]; Fred Perry v Genis [2015]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>s 15(3): Wishes of adult beneficiaries</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Court has regard to wishes of beneficiaries of full age; if dispute, majority view prevails (by value of combined interests); irrespective of value of interest</p></td><td><p>\u2014</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Court&#x27;s discretion</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>All relevant factors must be considered equally; court cannot pick and choose; orders available: sale; postponed sale; occupation; nature/extent of interest; CANNOT order buy-out</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>TOLATA 1996 s 14</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 6 \u2014 Leading Cases </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>at a Glance</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Case</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Topic</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Core Principle</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Re Caines deceased [1978]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Survivorship / will</p></td><td><p>Survivorship operates immediately on death; will has no effect on JT interest; any attempted testamentary provision of JT share = void</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Pink v Lawrence [1976]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Equitable title \u2014 express declaration</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Express declaration of TiC prevails over the four unities \u2014 parties&#x27; express intention governs equitable holding</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Lake v Craddock [1732]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Presumption of TiC</p></td><td><p>Where land is a business/commercial asset, rebuttable presumption of TiC in equity</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Bull v Bull [1955]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Presumption of TiC</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Unequal contributions to purchase price of non-domestic property \u2192 presumption of TiC in equity</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Goodman v Gallant [1986]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Effect of severance</p></td><td><p>Severance gives severing JT an equal aliquot share based on number of JTs at time of severance, not based on contributions</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Re Draper&#x27;s Conveyance [1969]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Severance by notice</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Divorce petition seeking immediate sale = unequivocal intention to sever; severance occurred</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Harris v Goddard [1983]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Severance by notice</p></td><td><p>&quot;Such order as may be just&quot; in divorce petition = not unequivocal; relates to future not immediate severance; no severance</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Kinch v Bullard [1999]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Service of notice</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Notice served when delivered to home; subsequent destruction of letter had no effect; severance already occurred</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>First National Security v Hegarty [1985]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Unilateral act \u2014 mortgage</p></td><td><p>Forged mortgage on entire property ineffective at law; treated as mortgage of husband&#x27;s equitable interest only; severed his share</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Burgess v Rawnsley [1975]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Mutual agreement / conduct</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Agreement to sell one JT&#x27;s interest suffices; significance is evidence of common intention; does not need to be enforceable contract</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Hunter v Babbage [1995]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Mutual agreement</p></td><td><p>Draft agreed consent order showing separate shares = severance by mutual agreement; need not be finalised</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Gore and Snell [1990]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Mutual conduct</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Negotiations alone insufficient; there was never a point both parties treated interests as separate</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Davis v Smith [2011]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Mutual conduct</p></td><td><p>Ongoing negotiations showing both parties treating interests as separate shares throughout = severance by mutual conduct</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Dunbabin</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> v </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Dunbabin</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> [2022]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Mutual conduct</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Making of mirror wills with provisions inconsistent with survivorship = mutual agreement/course of mutual conduct amounting to severance</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Re Evers&#x27; Trust [1980]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>TOLATA s 15(b)</p></td><td><p>Family home still capable of being used as one \u2014 purpose continuing; sale order refused</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Jones v Challenger [1961]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>TOLATA s 15(b)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Wife moved out; joint purpose of family home no longer continuing \u2014 sale ordered</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Bank of Ireland v Bell [2001]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>TOLATA s 15(1)(d)</p></td><td><p>Creditor owed \u00a3300k with no payments for 8 yrs; minor nearly 18; family home purpose minimal \u2014 sale ordered; creditor interest prevailed</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Putnam and Sons v Taylor [2009]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>TOLATA s 15(1)(d)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Family home purpose continuing but wife had enough equity to buy smaller property outright \u2014 sale ordered</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Fred Perry v Genis [2015]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>TOLATA s 15(1)(d)</p></td><td><p>Commercial interest took precedence over residential security; children&#x27;s school disrupted but sale still ordered (postponed one year)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Mortgage Corp v </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Shaire</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> [2001]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>TOLATA s 15(1)(d)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No presumption for or against sale at outset; all factors must be considered; creditor&#x27;s interest is just one factor</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>3. Flashcard Q&amp;A Pairs</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Question</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Answer</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is always imposed when land is co-owned?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>A trust of land (TOLATA 1996 s 1). Legal title held by trustees; equitable/beneficial title held by beneficiaries. Separate legal and equitable ownership.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What are the formalities for an express trust of land?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Must be evidenced in writing and signed by the declarant(s) (LPA 1925 s 53(1)(b)). Implied trusts (resulting/constructive) require no formalities (s 53(2) LPA).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What are the rules for legal title in co-ownership?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Maximum four legal owners (Trustee Act 1925 s 34(2)); all must be sui juris (full age and sound mind); must always be held as a joint tenancy \u2014 cannot be severed (LPA 1925 s 36(2)).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What are the four unities required for a joint tenancy?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Possession (entitled to the whole); Interest (same nature and duration); Time (interests vest simultaneously); Title (same document, or identical and interdependent documents). All four must be present for a JT.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is the right of survivorship and when does it operate?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Ius accrescendi: on death of a JT, their interest accrues automatically to the surviving JTs. Operates immediately on death \u2014 before any will can take effect. A will CANNOT dispose of a JT interest (Re Caines deceased [1978]).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>When is there a rebuttable presumption of tenancy in common in equity?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Where the land is a business asset (Lake v Craddock [1732]); or where the purchase price of non-domestic property was paid in unequal shares (Bull v Bull [1955]).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is severance and can it apply to the legal title?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Severance converts an equitable JT into a TiC. It can ONLY apply to the equitable title \u2014 never to the legal title (LPA 1925 s 36(2)). Must occur during the JT&#x27;s lifetime (a will cannot sever).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is the test for a valid notice of severance?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Must demonstrate an unequivocal and irrevocable intention to sever the equitable joint tenancy IMMEDIATELY (not in the future). Re Draper&#x27;s: immediate sale required = sufficient. Harris v Goddard: &quot;such order as may be just&quot; = not sufficient.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>When is a notice in writing deemed served?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>When delivered to the last known place of abode or business of the joint tenant \u2014 the notice does not need to have been read. Kinch v Bullard: destruction of letter after delivery had no effect; severance had already occurred.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What are the three Williams v Hensman modes of severance?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>(1) Unilateral act by one JT on their own share (total alienation/sale; partial alienation/mortgage; involuntary/bankruptcy). (2) Mutual agreement of all JTs (need not be enforceable contract). (3) Mutual conduct (course of dealing showing interests treated as separate).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is the effect of severance on the severing party&#x27;s share?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>They take an equal aliquot share: 1/n of the total where n = the number of JTs at the time of severance \u2014 NOT based on contributions (Goodman v Gallant [1986]). The remaining JTs continue to hold as JTs between themselves.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What did </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Dunbabin</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> v </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Dunbabin</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> [2022] decide about mirror wills?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Making of mirror wills with provisions inconsistent with survivorship (e.g. leaving the JT share to someone other than the other JT) can amount to mutual agreement or a course of mutual conduct sufficient to sever the equitable joint tenancy.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What orders can a court make under TOLATA 1996 s 14?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Order for sale (can be postponed); order as to who occupies; order as to nature/extent of a beneficiary&#x27;s interest. The court CANNOT order one beneficiary to buy out another.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>are</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> the s 15(1) TOLATA factors and which carries the most weight?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>(a) Creators&#x27; intentions (expressly created trusts only \u2014 NOT everyday co-ownership); (b) purpose of trust (still continuing? \u2014 Re Evers vs Jones v Challenger); (c) welfare of minors; (d) secured creditor interests. (d) carries greatest weight in practice (Bank of Ireland v Bell; Putnam v Taylor).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What happens when a court orders sale of co-owned land?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>A court sale order under TOLATA s 14 is an automatic overreaching event \u2014 the beneficiaries&#x27; interests in the land are transferred to an interest in the money paid on sale.</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>4. Common Exam Pitfalls &amp; Tricky Distinctions</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Pitfall / Distinction</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Explanation</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Legal title CANNOT be held as tenancy in common \u2014 ever</strong></span></p></td><td><p>LPA 1925 s 36(2) is absolute: the legal title in co-owned land MUST be held as a joint tenancy. It cannot be severed to create a legal TiC. This simplifies legal title and avoids complications on death. Only the equitable title can be a TiC.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>A will CANNOT dispose of a joint tenant&#x27;s interest</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Survivorship operates immediately on death (Re Caines deceased [1978]). By the time the will takes effect, the interest has already accrued to the surviving JTs. Any provision in a will purporting to pass a JT interest is void. The only way to pass the share under a will is to sever the JT during lifetime.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Severance only in lifetime \u2014 &quot;mutual conduct&quot; is hard to prove</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Severance must happen inter vivos. Making a will does not sever (Re Caines). Mutual conduct requires that both parties treated their interests as separate throughout \u2014 mere negotiations are insufficient (Gore and Snell). The threshold is high: both must have treated themselves as having distinct shares (Davis v Smith; Dunbabin v Dunbabin: mirror wills crossed the threshold).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Goodman v Gallant: severance gives equal, not proportionate, share</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>The severing JT takes 1/n of the equitable interest (n = number of JTs) \u2014 regardless of how much they contributed to the purchase price. This can be very significant on facts where one party paid much more than the other. Do not apply a contributions-based analysis to the post-severance share.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>s 15(1)(a) does NOT apply to everyday co-ownership</strong></span></p></td><td><p>The &quot;creators&#x27; intentions&quot; factor under s 15(1)(a) TOLATA only applies to expressly created lifetime trusts or will trusts, not to the implied trusts that arise automatically when people co-own their home. Do not apply this factor to a standard co-ownership dispute.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TOLATA s 14: court cannot order a buy-out</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>The court can order sale, postpone sale, regulate occupation, or determine the extent of interests \u2014 but it cannot order one co-owner to buy out another. If the parties want a buy-out, they must agree it themselves or rely on the sale proceeds.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Secured creditor interest and the &quot;purpose&quot; factor tension</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Where a property is still being used as a family home (purpose continuing), that weighs against sale. But recent case law (Bank of Ireland v Bell; Putnam v Taylor; Fred Perry v Genis) shows courts give significant weight to secured creditor interests, often overriding the continuing purpose and even welfare of minors. Always apply all s 15 factors, but signal the priority creditor interests have received.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Forged mortgage </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>severes</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> the forger&#x27;s equitable interest</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Where one JT fraudulently mortgages or sells the entire property, the attempted disposition of the whole is ineffective at law \u2014 but it is treated as a disposition of only the fraudulent JT&#x27;s equitable interest (First National Security v Hegarty). This severs their equitable share, creating a TiC between them and the other JTs.</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>"}], "Leases": [{"id": "leases-essential", "title": "W8: Essential Requirements of a Lease", "content": "<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>ESSENTIAL REQUIREMENTS OF A LEASE \u2014 REVISION NOTES</strong></span></p>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>1. Structured Topic Overview</strong></span></h3>\n<p>Lease analysis follows a clear logical sequence. An examiner expects you to address each stage in order:</p>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>STAGE 1 \u2014 LEASE OR LICENCE?</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>Identify whether the arrangement is a lease (proprietary) or a licence (personal)</li><li>Look at substance, not the label: Street v Mountford [1985]</li><li>Key distinction: leases are enforceable <em>in rem</em> (against the world); licences are enforceable <em>in personam</em> (against the grantor only)</li><li>Rent is NOT essential for a lease: LPA 1925 s 205(1)(xxvii); confirmed in Ashburn Anstalt v Arnold [1989]</li></ul>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>STAGE 2 \u2014 CERTAINTY OF TERM</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>Lease must be for a certain, ascertainable duration: either fixed or periodic</li><li>Fixed term: maximum duration known from the outset; neither party can end it early without a break clause</li><li>Periodic tenancy: runs from period to period; terminates on notice to quit; can be express or implied</li><li>Implied periodic tenancy: arises from possession + payment/acceptance of rent by reference to a period (Prudential Assurance v London Residuary Body [1992])</li><li>Uncertain duration = not a lease: Lace v Chantler [1944] (&quot;for the duration of the war&quot; \u2014 void for uncertainty)</li></ul>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>STAGE 3 \u2014 EXCLUSIVE POSSESSION</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>Right to exclude all others, including the landlord</li><li>Question of fact: courts examine the substance and reality of the arrangement</li><li>Sham clauses designed to defeat exclusive possession are disregarded</li><li>Indicators AGAINST exclusive possession: landlord retains key (with unrestricted access); landlord provides services (lodger); sharing clauses (if genuine); right to relocate</li><li>Sharing clause analysis (AG Securities v Vaughan; Antoniades v Villiers [1990]): size/nature of accommodation; relationship between occupiers; width of clause; whether clause has been exercised</li><li>Business tenancies: degree of physical control retained by landlord is a key factor (Esso v Fumegrange [1994])</li></ul>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>STAGE 4 \u2014 MULTIPLE OCCUPIERS: JOINT TENANCY OR LICENCE?</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>Multiple occupiers can hold a joint tenancy if together they can exclude all others including the landlord</li><li>Four unities must all be present: Possession, Interest, Time, Title (AG Securities v Vaughan [1990])</li><li>If any unity is missing: no joint tenancy; if no individual tenancy either \u2192 only individual licensees</li><li>Separate documents can satisfy unity of title if they are identical and interdependent (Antoniades v Villiers)</li></ul>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>STAGE 5 \u2014 FACTORS DEFEATING A LEASE</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>Even if certainty of term and exclusive possession are present, a lease can be defeated by:</li><li>No intention to create legal relations (ICLR): family arrangement; act of friendship; act of generosity \u2014 but market rent or formality can rebut this (Facchini v Bryson [1952])</li><li>Service occupancy: occupier must reside there for better performance of employment duties; rent may still be paid (Norris v Checksfield [1991])</li></ul>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>STAGE 6 \u2014 FORMALITIES TO CREATE A LEGAL LEASE</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>General rule: deed required (LPA 1925 s 52; LP(MP)A 1989 s 1)</li><li>Over 7 years: deed + compulsory registration (LRA 2002 s 27(2)(b)(i)); failure to register = no legal leasehold estate (s 27(1))</li><li>7 years or less: deed required, no registration needed; overriding interest binding new owner (LRA 2002 Sch 3 para 1)</li><li>Short lease exception (s 54(2) LPA 1925): 3 years or less, in possession, at best rent, no fine/premium \u2014 no deed required (parol lease)</li><li>Equitable lease: arises where legal lease fails but there is a valid s 2 LP(MP)A 1989 document + specific performance available (Walsh v Lonsdale [1882])</li></ul>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>STAGE </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>7</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong> \u2014 </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>IF THERE IS A LEASE, IS IT ENFORCEABLE AGAINST A NEW OWNER?</strong></span></p>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>2. Summary Revision Tables</strong></span></h3>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 1 \u2014 Key Definitions &amp; Statutory Provisions</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Concept</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Definition / Provision</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Source</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Lease / tenancy</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Grant of a temporary right to use and enjoy land exclusively; a &quot;term of years absolute&quot;</p></td><td><p>LPA 1925 s 1(1)(b)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Sublease / underlease</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>A lease granted out of a superior lease (not out of the freehold)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Licence</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Personal permission to be on another&#x27;s land; not proprietary; only enforceable against the grantor</p></td><td><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Security of tenure</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Right of occupants to remain after the formal arrangement ends and request a new lease</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Rent</strong></span></p></td><td><p>NOT essential for a lease</p></td><td><p>LPA 1925 s 205(1)(xxvii); Ashburn Anstalt v Arnold [1989]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Certainty of term</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>The lease must be granted for a certain, ascertainable duration \u2014 either fixed or periodic</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Street v Mountford [1985]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Exclusive possession</strong></span></p></td><td><p>The right to exclude all others from the property, including the landlord</p></td><td><p>Street v Mountford [1985]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Fixed term</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Maximum duration of the arrangement known from outset; cannot be unilaterally ended early without a break clause</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Periodic tenancy</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Lease for one period (e.g. weekly/monthly/yearly); extends automatically until notice to quit is given</p></td><td><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Break clause</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Right for either/both parties to terminate lease early; may be conditional; requires notice</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Parol lease</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Short lease created without a deed under LPA 1925 s 54(2); does not require registration</p></td><td><p>LPA 1925 s 54(2)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Service occupancy</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Occupation by an employee required for better performance of their duties; not a tenancy even if rent is paid</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Norris v Checksfield [1991]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Lodger</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Occupier whose landlord provides services (cleaning, linen etc.); never has exclusive possession</p></td><td><p>Marchant v Charters [1977]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Joint tenancy (lease)</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Multiple occupiers who together can exclude all others; must hold the four unities</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>AG Securities v Vaughan [1990]</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 2 \u2014 Lease vs Licence: Key Distinctions</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Feature</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Lease</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Licence</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Nature of right</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Proprietary right in land</p></td><td><p>Personal permission only</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Enforceability</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Enforceable in rem \u2014 against third parties</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Enforceable in personam \u2014 against grantor only</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Nuisance / trespass</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Tenant can sue third parties</p></td><td><p>Licensee cannot sue third parties</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Security of tenure</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Tenant may have statutory security of tenure</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No security of tenure</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Statutory protection</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Various statutory protections for tenants</p></td><td><p>No statutory protection for licensees</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Test (since 1985)</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Substance of arrangement: certain term + exclusive possession (Street v Mountford)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Absence of certain term and/or exclusive possession</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Label / name</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Irrelevant \u2014 courts look at substance not label</p></td><td><p>Cannot create a licence by calling it one</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 3 \u2014 Certainty of Term</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Type</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule / Detail</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Authority</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>General requirement</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Must be known from the outset when the arrangement will end; cannot be uncertain</p></td><td><p>Lace v Chantler [1944]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Lace v Chantler [1944]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>&quot;For the duration of the war&quot; was void for uncertainty; term not ascertainable at the outset</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Lace v Chantler [1944]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Fixed term</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Maximum duration known from outset; neither party can end it unilaterally without a break clause</p></td><td><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Break clause</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Right to end lease early; may be conditional; usually requires notice to be served on the other party</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Periodic tenancy (general)</strong></span></p></td><td><p>One period at a time (weekly, monthly, quarterly, yearly); extends automatically; ends on notice to quit</p></td><td><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Implied periodic tenancy</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Arises from possession + payment/acceptance of rent; period determined by how rent is calculated (not how often paid)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Prudential Assurance v London Residuary Body [1992]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Prudential Assurance [1992]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Lease &quot;until land needed for road widening&quot;  was an uncertain period but held to be yearly periodic tenancy arising from possession and rent paid by reference to a year</p></td><td><p>Prudential Assurance v London Residuary Body [1992]</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 4 \u2014 Exclusive Possession: Indicators </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>For</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> and Against</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Indicator</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Authority</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>FOR \u2014 Restricted landlord access</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Landlord&#x27;s access limited to specific purpose (e.g. repairs only) = evidence of exclusive possession</p></td><td><p>Street v Mountford [1985]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>AGAINST \u2014 Key retention (unrestricted)</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Landlord retains key + unrestricted access = against exclusive possession; purpose of key retention is the key factor</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Aslan v Murphy [1990]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>AGAINST \u2014 Landlord provides services</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Attendance or services (cleaning, linen etc.) = licence not tenancy; occupier is a &quot;lodger&quot;</p></td><td><p>Marchant v Charters [1977]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>AGAINST \u2014 Sharing clause (genuine)</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Right to share or introduce others defeats exclusive possession only if clause is genuine (not a sham)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>AG Securities v Vaughan [1990]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>AGAINST \u2014 Right to relocate (genuine)</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Right to move tenant to alternative accommodation defeats exclusive possession</p></td><td><p>Dresden Estates v Collinson [1988]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Sham clauses disregarded</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Courts disregard clauses inserted only to make a lease look like a licence; examine the reality and substance</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Antoniades v Villiers [1990]</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 5 \u2014 Sharing Clause Analysis: Genuine vs Sham (Antoniades Test)</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Factor</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>How Courts Assess It</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Size and nature of accommodation</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Would it be physically feasible for the landlord to introduce others to share? (A very small room \u2014 unlikely to be genuine)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Relationship between occupiers</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Would it be appropriate/realistic to introduce a stranger given the existing relationship between the occupiers? (Couple sharing \u2014 sharing clause likely a sham)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Width of the clause</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Broadly drafted clauses (e.g. right to introduce &quot;anyone&quot;) are more likely to be treated as shams; narrow/specific clauses are more credible</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Whether the clause has been exercised</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>If never exercised, this is evidence it was never intended to be used \u2014 i.e. it is a sham clause</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 6 \u2014 AG Securities v Vaughan vs Antoniades v Villiers [1990]: Contrast</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Feature</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>AG Securities v Vaughan</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Antoniades v Villiers</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Occupiers</strong></span></p></td><td><p>4 unrelated occupiers</p></td><td><p>Couple in a relationship</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Agreements</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Separate agreements at different times; different rents</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Separate but identical and interdependent agreements signed on the same day</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Sharing clause</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Genuine \u2014 only 1 of 4 rooms; other occupiers genuinely introduced at different times</p></td><td><p>Sham \u2014 one-bedroom flat; not feasible to introduce a stranger to share with a couple</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Four unities present?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No \u2014 time and title missing (different times, different terms)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Yes \u2014 identical and interdependent documents treated as one</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Outcome</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Individual licences only \u2014 no joint tenancy</p></td><td><p>Joint tenancy \u2014 lease</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Key principle</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Separate agreements at different times can break unity of time/title</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Separate documents treated as one if identical and interdependent; sharing clause disregarded as sham</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 7 \u2014 Four Unities of Joint Tenancy</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Unity</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Requirement</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Note</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Possession</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Each occupier entitled to occupy the whole premises; no-one has exclusive use of any part</p></td><td><p>If each has exclusive possession of a defined part \u2192 possible individual leases instead</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Interest</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Same leasehold interest, same term, same conditions, jointly liable for whole rent</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Joint liability: if one leaves, remaining occupiers liable for all the rent, not just their share</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Time</strong></span></p></td><td><p>All occupiers&#x27; interests must begin at the same time</p></td><td><p>AG Securities: different start dates = no unity of time \u2192 no joint tenancy</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Title</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>All interests derive from the same document, or separate documents that are identical and interdependent</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Antoniades: identical and interdependent documents satisfy this even if technically separate</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Missing unity</strong></span></p></td><td><p>If any one of the four unities is absent: no joint tenancy; if no individual tenancy either \u2192 individual licensees sharing</p></td><td><p>AG Securities v Vaughan [1990]</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 8 \u2014 Factors That Defeat a Lease (Even if Requirements Met)</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Defeating Factor</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Authority</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>No intention to create legal relations (ICLR)</strong></span></p></td><td><p>No ICLR where: family arrangement; act of friendship; act of generosity. BUT market rent and/or formality of agreement evidences ICLR even between family/friends</p></td><td><p>Facchini v Bryson [1952]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Service occupancy</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Where employee must occupy premises for better performance of duties \u2014 not a tenancy even if rent paid. Test: is occupation necessary for the job, or merely a perk of the job?</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Norris v Checksfield [1991]; Royal Philanthropic v County [1985]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Norris v Checksfield [1991]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Lorry driver required premises to perform job duties \u2192 service occupancy; no lease</p></td><td><p>Norris v Checksfield [1991]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Royal Philanthropic v County [1985]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Teacher&#x27;s house near school was a perk of the job, not necessary for duties \u2192 lease (no service occupancy)</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Royal Philanthropic v County [1985]</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 9 \u2014 Formalities to Create a Lease</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Type of Lease</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Formality Requirement</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Provision / Effect</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>General rule (all legal leases)</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Deed (LPA 1925 s 52) complying with LP(MP)A 1989 s 1: in writing; clear it is a deed; signed and witnessed</p></td><td><p>LP(MP)A 1989 s 1; LPA 1925 s 52</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Over 7 years</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Deed + compulsory substantive registration at Land Registry (LRA 2002 s 27(2)(b)(i))</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Failure to register = no legal leasehold estate created (LRA 2002 s 27(1))</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>7 years or less</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Deed required; no registration needed</p></td><td><p>Binding on new freehold owner as overriding interest (LRA 2002 Sch 3 para 1)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Short lease exception \u2014 3 years or less (s 54(2) LPA 1925)</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No deed required provided: (i) takes effect in possession; (ii) granted at best rent (market rent); (iii) no fine or premium</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Known as &quot;parol leases&quot;; no registration needed; still legal leases</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Parol leases (types)</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Short fixed-term leases; express periodic tenancies; implied periodic tenancies (where individual period is 3 years or less)</p></td><td><p>LPA 1925 s 54(2)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Equitable lease</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Arises where: (i) legal lease fails (no valid deed / not registered); AND (ii) valid s 2 LP(MP)A 1989 document exists + specific performance available</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Walsh v Lonsdale [1882]: equity prevails over common law where conflict</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 10 \u2014 Business Tenancies: Lease vs Licence</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Point</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule / Detail</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Street v Mountford applies</strong></span></p></td><td><p>The Street v Mountford test (certain term + exclusive possession) applies equally to non-residential/business tenancies</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Importance</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Business tenants may be protected by the Landlord and Tenant Act 1954 \u2014 entitles them to remain and request a new lease at end of term; only applies to tenants, not licensees</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Key factor in business context</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Degree of physical control the landlord retains over the property and the conduct of the business \u2014 more control = less likely to be exclusive possession</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Label more readily accepted</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Courts more willing to accept a &quot;licence&quot; label in commercial contexts due to greater equality of bargaining power between parties</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Esso v Fumegrange [1994]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Esso retained control: could alter premises, change shop layout \u2192 Fumegrange did not have exclusive possession of the service stations \u2192 licence, not lease</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 11 \u2014 All Leading Cases </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>at a Glance</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Case</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Topic</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Core Principle</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Street v Mountford [1985]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Lease or licence; exclusive possession</p></td><td><p>Substance not label; for a lease: certain term + exclusive possession; HoL overruled label-based approach</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Ashburn Anstalt v Arnold [1989]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Rent</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Rent is NOT essential for a lease (confirming LPA 1925 s 205(1)(xxvii))</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Lace v Chantler [1944]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Certainty of term</p></td><td><p>&quot;For the duration of the war&quot; \u2014 void for uncertainty of term; fails certainty requirement</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Prudential Assurance v London Residuary Body [1992]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Certainty of term / implied periodic tenancy</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Lease to last until &quot;land needed for road widening&quot; void for uncertainty; yearly periodic tenancy arose from possession + rent calculated by year</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Aslan v Murphy [1990]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Exclusive possession \u2014 key retention</p></td><td><p>Purpose of key retention is the key factor; emergency-only or arranged access \u2192 exclusive possession may still exist</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Marchant v Charters [1977]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Exclusive possession \u2014 services</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Landlord providing services (cleaning, linen) = licence, not tenancy; occupier is a lodger</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Dresden Estates v Collinson [1988]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Exclusive possession \u2014 relocation</p></td><td><p>Right to relocate tenant defeats exclusive possession; sham relocation clauses are disregarded</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>AG Securities v Vaughan [1990]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Multiple occupiers / four unities</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>4 unrelated occupiers on separate staggered agreements at different rents \u2192 no unity of time/title \u2192 individual licensees, not joint tenants</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Antoniades v Villiers [1990]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Multiple occupiers / sham clauses</p></td><td><p>Couple; separate but identical interdependent agreements \u2192 unity of title satisfied; sharing clause a sham (one-bedroom flat) \u2192 joint tenancy</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Facchini v Bryson [1952]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Defeating a lease \u2014 no ICLR</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No ICLR: family arrangements, acts of friendship/generosity; rebutted by market rent and/or formality of agreement</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Norris v Checksfield [1991]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Defeating a lease \u2014 service occupancy</p></td><td><p>Lorry driver required premises to perform duties \u2192 service occupancy; no tenancy</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Royal Philanthropic v County [1985]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Defeating a lease \u2014 service occupancy</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Teacher&#x27;s accommodation near school was a perk, not necessary for duties \u2192 tenancy, not service occupancy</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Esso Petroleum v Fumegrange [1994]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Business tenancies / exclusive possession</p></td><td><p>Esso retained physical control over premises and business \u2192 no exclusive possession \u2192 licence</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Walsh v Lonsdale [1882]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Equitable lease</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Where legal lease fails but valid s 2 LP(MP)A 1989 document + specific performance available \u2192 equitable lease; equity prevails over common law</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>3. Flashcard Q&amp;A Pairs</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Question</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Answer</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What are the two essential requirements for a lease under Street v Mountford [1985]?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Certainty of term; and exclusive possession. Rent is NOT essential (LPA 1925 s 205(1)(xxvii); Ashburn Anstalt v Arnold).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>How do courts distinguish a lease from a licence since Street v Mountford?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Look at the substance, not the label. Parties cannot change the effect of an arrangement by calling it a licence \u2014 if certain term and exclusive possession are present, it is a lease.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What are the two ways certainty of term can be satisfied?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Fixed term (maximum duration known from outset) or periodic tenancy (runs period-to-period; terminates on notice to quit).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>How does an implied periodic tenancy arise?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>From possession + payment and acceptance of rent; the period of the tenancy is determined by reference to how the rent is calculated, not how often it is paid (Prudential Assurance v London Residuary Body [1992]).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Why did the arrangement in Lace v Chantler [1944] fail?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>The lease was &quot;for the duration of the war&quot; \u2014 this was not a certain term because the maximum duration was not known from the outset.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What does exclusive possession mean?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>The right to exclude all others from the property, including the landlord.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Is a landlord retaining a key fatal to exclusive possession?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Not automatically \u2014 Aslan v Murphy [1990]: the purpose for which the key is retained is the key factor. Emergency-only or arranged use of the key is consistent with exclusive possession.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>When does a landlord providing services defeat exclusive possession?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Where the landlord provides attendance or services such as cleaning and changing linen (Marchant v Charters [1977]). The occupier is a &quot;lodger&quot; and never has exclusive possession.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What are the four factors used to assess whether a sharing clause is a sham?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>(1) Size and nature of the accommodation \u2014 would sharing be feasible? (2) Relationship between occupiers \u2014 would introducing others be appropriate? (3) Width of the clause. (4) Whether the clause has ever been exercised.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What right does a right to relocate confer on the landlord, and what is its effect?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>The right to move the tenant to alternative accommodation defeats exclusive possession (Dresden Estates v Collinson [1988]); if the clause is a sham, it is disregarded.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What are the four unities required for a joint tenancy?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Possession (each entitled to the whole); Interest (same term, conditions, jointly liable for all rent); Time (interests start together); Title (same document or identical and interdependent documents).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>If one of the four unities is missing, what is the consequence?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No joint tenancy. If there is also no individual tenancy of any part, the occupiers can only be individual licensees sharing with each other (AG Securities v Vaughan [1990]).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>How did the court distinguish AG Securities v Vaughan from Antoniades v Villiers?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>AG Securities: 4 unrelated people, staggered agreements at different times and rents \u2014 no unity of time or title \u2014 individual licences. Antoniades: couple, identical and interdependent agreements signed the same day \u2014 unity of title satisfied; sharing clause was a sham \u2014 joint tenancy.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What two factors can defeat a lease even where certain term and exclusive possession are both present?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>(1) No intention to create legal relations (family/friendship/generosity arrangements \u2014 rebutted by market rent or formality). (2) Service occupancy (employee must live there for better performance of duties).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is the test for a service occupancy?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>The occupier must be required to occupy the premises for the better performance of their employment duties \u2014 not merely as a perk of the job (Norris v Checksfield vs Royal Philanthropic v County).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What are the formality requirements for a legal lease over 7 years?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Deed complying with LP(MP)A 1989 s 1 (in writing; clearly a deed; signed and witnessed) + compulsory substantive registration at Land Registry (LRA 2002 s 27(2)(b)(i)). Failure to register = no legal leasehold estate.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What are the three conditions for the short lease exception under LPA 1925 s 54(2)?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>(1) Lease for 3 years or less; (2) takes effect in possession (immediately); (3) at best/market rent; (4) no fine or premium. If all met: no deed required; still a legal lease.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>How does an equitable lease arise?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Where a legal lease fails (no valid deed, or not registered), but a valid s 2 LP(MP)A 1989 document exists and specific performance is available \u2192 equitable lease on same terms (Walsh v Lonsdale [1882]).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is the significance of LRA 2002 Sch 3 para 1 for leases of 7 years or less?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Leases of 7 years or less that are not registered still take effect as legal leases and are binding on a new freehold owner as overriding interests.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>How does the business tenancy context modify the Street v Mountford approach?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Certain term and exclusive possession still required; but courts focus on degree of physical control the landlord retains over the property and business; courts more willing to accept a licence label due to equality of bargaining power (Esso v Fumegrange [1994]).</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>4. Common Exam Pitfalls &amp; Tricky Distinctions</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Pitfall / Distinction</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Explanation</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Rent is NOT essential \u2014 do not assume it is</strong></span></p></td><td><p>A very common error: students assume rent is a third requirement for a lease. It is not. LPA 1925 s 205(1)(xxvii) is explicit, and Ashburn Anstalt v Arnold [1989] confirms it. Only certainty of term and exclusive possession are the two essential requirements from Street v Mountford.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Label of the agreement is irrelevant</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Parties cannot create a licence simply by calling their arrangement a licence (Street v Mountford). The court will always look at substance. A &quot;licence fee&quot; is still rent; a &quot;licence&quot; that grants certain term + exclusive possession is still a lease. Never accept the label at face value in a problem question.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Period of implied tenancy: how rent is calculated, not how it is paid</strong></span></p></td><td><p>The period of an implied periodic tenancy depends on how rent is calculated, not the intervals at which it is physically paid. Monthly payments may give rise to a yearly periodic tenancy if the rent is expressed as an annual sum. Always check how the rent is expressed, not just when it is collected.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Sham clauses must be identified and disregarded</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>A sharing clause or relocation clause that exists only to make a lease look like a licence will be disregarded by the court (Antoniades v Villiers). Apply the four-factor sham analysis: size of accommodation; relationship between occupiers; width of drafting; whether ever exercised. Do not automatically accept such clauses at face value.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Key retention: purpose matters, not mere fact</strong></span></p></td><td><p>The fact that a landlord retains a key does not automatically defeat exclusive possession (Aslan v Murphy [1990]). The question is why the key is retained and what access it confers \u2014 unrestricted access defeats exclusive possession; access only in emergencies or by arrangement is consistent with it.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Four unities: all four must be present</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>For a joint tenancy, all four unities must be present \u2014 miss any one and there is no joint tenancy. AG Securities v Vaughan failed on time and title because the occupiers entered into separate agreements at different times and at different rents. Carefully check each unity before concluding a joint tenancy exists.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Separate documents can still satisfy unity of title</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Do not assume that separate documents automatically destroy unity of title. If the documents are identical and interdependent, the court will treat them as one (Antoniades v Villiers). The question is whether the documents were intended to operate together as a single arrangement.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Service occupancy: necessity, not mere benefit</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>The test is not whether the employee benefits from living on the premises \u2014 it is whether occupation is necessary for the better performance of their duties (Norris v Checksfield). A perk of the job (Royal Philanthropic v County) is insufficient: the teacher could have performed duties without living nearby. Apply this distinction carefully.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Formalities: the s 54(2) exception has three strict conditions</strong></span></p></td><td><p>The short lease exception applies only if all three conditions are met: 3 years or less; takes effect in possession (not in the future); at best/market rent; no fine or premium. If any condition fails, the exception does not apply and a deed is required. &quot;Best rent&quot; means market rent \u2014 a concessionary rent will not qualify.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Equitable lease vs no lease at all</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>A failed legal lease does not automatically become an equitable lease. Two further requirements must be met: (1) there must be a valid s 2 LP(MP)A 1989 document (in writing, all terms, signed by both parties); and (2) specific performance must be available as a remedy. Without both, there is no equitable lease \u2014 only, at best, a periodic tenancy arising from possession and payment of rent.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Business tenancy: Street v Mountford still applies</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Do not overlook the fact that Street v Mountford applies equally to non-residential leases. The same two-stage analysis (certain term; exclusive possession) must be carried out. The only modification is that courts give more weight to the label in commercial contexts due to equality of bargaining power \u2014 but this is not determinative.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>No ICLR: family/friendship relationship does not automatically defeat lease</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>A family or friendly relationship between the parties does not automatically mean there is no ICLR. Where the agreement has a degree of formality or where market rent is paid, ICLR can still be found (Facchini v Bryson). Do not conclude &quot;no lease&quot; simply because the parties are related.</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>"}, {"id": "leases-covenants-notes", "title": "W9: Leasehold Covenants", "content": "<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>COVENANTS IN LEASES \u2014 COMPREHENSIVE REVISION NOTES</strong></span></p>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>1. Structured Topic Overview</strong></span></h3>\n<p>Leasehold covenants analysis requires identifying: (i) the type of covenant; (ii) whether the lease is old or new; (iii) who is seeking to enforce; (iv) the applicable rules on privity and transmission.</p>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>STAGE 1 \u2014 THE FOUR MAIN LEASEHOLD COVENANTS</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>Repair: tenant must keep premises in condition a reasonably minded owner would, having regard to character/type/age of premises and express wording (Proudfoot v Hart [1890])</li><li>Alterations: structural vs non-structural; absolute/qualified/fully qualified covenant distinction</li><li>User: restricts use to specified purpose; landlord controls occupation type</li><li>Alienation: assignment (transfer of lease by deed); subletting (new underlease); parting with possession; charging</li></ul>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>STAGE 2 \u2014 COVENANT TYPE: ABSOLUTE / QUALIFIED / FULLY QUALIFIED</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>Absolute: tenant completely prohibited; landlord can refuse any request; no duty to consider</li><li>Qualified: tenant may request consent; landlord has no obligation to give consent</li><li>Fully qualified: landlord&#x27;s consent not to be unreasonably withheld; test of reasonableness applies (International Drilling Fluids v Louisville [1986])</li></ul>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>STAGE 3 \u2014 PRIVITY OF CONTRACT AND ESTATE (OLD LEASES \u2014 pre-1 Jan 1996)</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>Privity of contract: original L and T liable for the full duration of the lease \u2014 even after assignment</li><li>Privity of estate: covenants that &quot;touch and concern&quot; the land enforceable between current L and T</li><li>&quot;Touch and concern&quot;: relates to L/T relationship; benefits parties in their capacity as L/T; personal covenants do not pass</li></ul>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>STAGE 4 \u2014 LTCA 1995 (NEW LEASES \u2014 on/after 1 Jan 1996)</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>S 3: automatic transmission of benefit AND burden of ALL covenants (except personal) to assignee of lease AND reversioner</li><li>S 5: automatic release of outgoing tenant on assignment (unless excluded assignment under s 11)</li><li>No automatic release for landlord (s 6): must apply to tenant; if refused, apply to court (s 8)</li><li>AGA (s 16): condition of landlord&#x27;s consent to assignment; outgoing T guarantees immediate assignee&#x27;s obligations only</li><li>S 17: landlord must serve notice of fixed charge claim on former tenant within 6 months of charge becoming due</li><li>S 18: former tenants/guarantors not liable for unanticipated lease variations</li><li>S 19: former tenant sued under s 17 may request overriding lease (becomes immediate landlord of defaulting party)</li></ul>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-navy\"><strong>STAGE 5 \u2014 SUBLEASES</strong></span></p>\n<ul class=\"notes-list\"><li>No direct relationship between head landlord and subtenant</li><li>S 3(5) LTCA 1995: restrictive covenants in new leases enforceable against any owner or occupier (but NOT positive covenants)</li><li>Head landlord forfeiting head lease = automatic termination of sublease (subject to relief claim)</li></ul>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>2. Summary Revision Tables</strong></span></h3>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 1 \u2014 Key Definitions</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Term</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Definition</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Source</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Leasehold covenant</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Promise contained in a lease given by a landlord or tenant</p></td><td><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Privity of contract</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Legal relationship between original contracting parties; original L and T liable for full lease term under old rules</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Contract law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Privity of estate</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Relationship between current L and current T while each holds their respective legal estate; allows covenants touching and concerning the land to be enforced</p></td><td><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Touch and concern</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Covenants relating to the L/T relationship; benefit parties in their capacity as L/T; personal covenants do not touch and concern</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>General law (old leases)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Old lease</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Lease granted before 1 January 1996; governed by privity of contract and estate rules</p></td><td><p>Pre-LTCA 1995</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>New lease</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Lease granted on or after 1 January 1996; governed by LTCA 1995</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>LTCA 1995</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Authorised guarantee agreement (AGA)</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Guarantee by outgoing tenant of the immediate assignee&#x27;s obligations only; condition of landlord&#x27;s consent to assignment under new lease</p></td><td><p>LTCA 1995 s 16</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Excluded assignment</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Assignment in breach of alienation covenant (e.g. without landlord&#x27;s consent); no automatic release under s 5 LTCA</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>LTCA 1995 s 11</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Overriding lease (s 19)</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Lease granted to a former tenant who has been required to pay a fixed charge under s 17; makes the former tenant the immediate landlord of the defaulting assignee</p></td><td><p>LTCA 1995 s 19</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Alienation</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Disposing of the whole or part of a leasehold interest: assignment, subletting, parting with possession, charging/mortgaging, surrendering</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Underlease / sublease</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Lease granted by a tenant out of their own lease; headlease remains; tenant remains responsible to head landlord</p></td><td><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Headlease</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>The superior lease out of which the underlease is granted</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Fixed charge (s 17)</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Arrears of rent, service charges, insurance premiums; NOT unascertained liabilities or damages requiring court order</p></td><td><p>LTCA 1995 s 17</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 2 \u2014 The Four Main Leasehold Covenants</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Covenant</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Rule</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Authority</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Repair</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Tenant must keep premises in condition a reasonably minded owner would, having regard to: (i) character/type at commencement of lease; (ii) age; (iii) express wording. Does not increase or decrease with change in neighbourhood. Obligation to put in repair first if in disrepair at commencement. Repair \u2260 renewal of substantially the whole</p></td><td><p>Proudfoot v Hart [1890]; Lurcott v Wakely [1911]; Brew Brothers v Snax [1970]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Alterations</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Unless lease says otherwise: tenant free to alter subject to doctrine of waste (no devaluing alterations). Structural/non-structural distinction common. Often subject to absolute/qualified/fully qualified covenant</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>General law; International Drilling Fluids [1986]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>User</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Restricts use of premises to specified purpose. Landlord controls what type of occupation is permitted. Often subject to absolute/qualified/fully qualified covenant</p></td><td><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Alienation</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Restricts assignment, subletting, parting with possession, charging. If lease silent: benefit of lease freely assignable. Covenant construed in tenant&#x27;s favour: anti-assignment \u2260 anti-subletting (Church v Brown [1808]); anti-subletting of whole \u2260 anti-subletting of part (Wilson v Rosenthal [1906])</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Church v Brown [1808]; Wilson v Rosenthal [1906]</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 3 \u2014 Absolute, Qualified and Fully Qualified Covenants</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Type</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Example Wording</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Absolute</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Tenant completely prohibited; landlord can refuse at will with no reason required; landlord can even ignore requests</p></td><td><p>&quot;The Tenant shall not underlet any part of the Premises&quot;</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Qualified</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Tenant may request consent; landlord NOT obliged to give consent; no duty of reasonableness</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>&quot;The Tenant shall not make any alterations without the consent of the Landlord&quot;</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Fully qualified</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Landlord must not unreasonably withhold consent; test of reasonableness applies; landlord cannot refuse on grounds unrelated to L/T relationship</p></td><td><p>&quot;...without the consent of the Landlord, such consent not to be unreasonably withheld&quot;</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Reasonableness test</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>International Drilling Fluids [1986]: landlord NOT entitled to refuse on grounds unrelated to landlord and tenant relationship. E.g. disliking assignee personally, or supporting different football team = unreasonable. Ability to pay rent, references = reasonable grounds</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>International Drilling Fluids v Louisville [1986]</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 4 \u2014 Repair: Key Distinctions</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Issue</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Key Case</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Standard of repair</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Condition a reasonably minded owner would maintain; having regard to: character/type of premises at lease commencement; age; express covenant wording</p></td><td><p>Proudfoot v Hart [1890]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Disrepair at commencement</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Obligation to PUT premises in repair first, then keep them in repair \u2014 can be very onerous if premises are in disrepair when lease begins</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Schedule of condition</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Limits obligation: tenant under no obligation to put premises in better state of repair than evidenced by annexed schedule of condition (photographs + description)</p></td><td><p>General law</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Repair vs renewal</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Question of degree: &quot;repair is restoration by renewal or replacement of subsidiary parts; renewal is reconstruction of the entirety&quot; \u2014 rebuilding substantially the whole = renewal not repair; falls outside repairing covenant</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Lurcott v Wakely [1911]</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Cost vs value test</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Where cost of works approximates to value of premises, works may be classed as renewal not repair \u2014 outside covenant</p></td><td><p>Brew Brothers v Snax (Ross) [1970]</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 5 \u2014 Old Leases vs New Leases: Enforceability of Covenants</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Feature</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Old Lease (pre-1 Jan 1996)</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>New Lease (on/after 1 Jan 1996 \u2014 LTCA 1995)</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Governing law</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Privity of contract and privity of estate</p></td><td><p>LTCA 1995</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Original tenant liability after assignment</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>CONTINUES for full lease duration \u2014 liable for own and assignee&#x27;s breaches; greatest hardship</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>ENDS on assignment (s 5 LTCA automatic release); remains liable only for breaches during own period of occupation (s 23(1))</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Original landlord liability after assignment</strong></span></p></td><td><p>CONTINUES for full lease duration</p></td><td><p>No automatic release; must apply to tenant (s 6); if refused, apply to court (s 8)</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Covenants that run with lease</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>&quot;Touch and concern&quot; the land; personal covenants do not pass</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>ALL covenants (except those &quot;expressed to be personal to any person&quot;) pass automatically under s 3 LTCA</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Running to new tenant (assignee)</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Touch and concern covenants run under privity of estate</p></td><td><p>Benefit and burden of ALL covenants pass automatically under s 3</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Running to new landlord (reversioner)</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Touch and concern covenants run under privity of estate</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Benefit and burden of ALL covenants pass automatically under s 3</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Excluded assignment</strong></span></p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td><td><p>Assignment in breach of alienation covenant; s 5 automatic release does NOT apply; tenant remains liable</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>AGA</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Direct covenant from assignee to landlord commonly required</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Condition of consent; guarantees immediate assignee&#x27;s obligations only; further AGA required on subsequent assignment (s 16 LTCA)</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 6 \u2014 LTCA 1995 Retrospective Provisions (Apply to ALL Leases)</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Provision</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Notes</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>S 17: Tenant default notice</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Landlord must notify former tenant of fixed charge claim within 6 months of the charge becoming due; failure to serve = precluded from claiming</p></td><td><p>Fixed charge: rent arrears; service charges; insurance premiums. NOT unascertained/damages-requiring-court-order liabilities</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>S 18: Liability for variations</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Former tenants and guarantors NOT liable for additional amounts arising from lease variations made after assignment that could not have been anticipated at the time the lease was entered into</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Anticipated variation example: rent review pursuant to clause in original lease = still liable</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>S 19: Overriding lease</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Former tenant required to pay under s 17 may request an overriding lease from landlord; landlord must grant within reasonable time; former tenant becomes immediate landlord of defaulting assignee</p></td><td><p>Term = remaining term + 3 days; same covenants (excluding personal ones); enables former tenant to manage, forfeit, or re-let</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 7 \u2014 Subleases: Enforcement and Key Rules</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Issue</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Rule</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Direct relationship</strong></span></p></td><td><p>No privity of contract or estate between head landlord and subtenant; head landlord cannot directly enforce covenants against subtenant as a general rule</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>S 3(5) LTCA 1995</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Restrictive covenants in new leases may be enforced against any owner or occupier of the premises \u2014 including a subtenant; positive covenants cannot be enforced directly against a subtenant</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Tenant&#x27;s protection</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Tenant (head lessee) remains responsible to head landlord for subtenant&#x27;s breaches; typically includes subtenant covenant to observe headlease obligations in underlease</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Forfeiture of headlease</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>If head landlord forfeits the headlease, the sublease is automatically terminated; threat of this incentivises subtenant compliance with head lease covenants</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Landlord&#x27;s protection</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Prudent head landlord conditions consent to subletting on subtenant entering direct covenants with head landlord to observe all headlease covenants; creates direct contractual enforcement right</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>TABLE 8 \u2014 All Leading Cases </strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>at a Glance</strong></span></p>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Case</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Topic</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Core Principle</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Proudfoot v Hart [1890]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Repair standard</p></td><td><p>Standard of repair: reasonably minded owner, having regard to character/type of premises at commencement, age, and express wording</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Lurcott</strong></span><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong> v Wakely [1911]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Repair vs renewal</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>&quot;Repair is restoration by renewal of subsidiary parts; renewal is reconstruction of the entirety&quot; \u2014 whole or substantially whole must be replaced to be renewal</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Brew Brothers v Snax (Ross) [1970]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Repair vs renewal</p></td><td><p>Where cost of works \u2248 value of premises \u2192 works are renewal not repair; outside tenant&#x27;s repairing covenant</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Church v Brown [1808]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Alienation \u2014 construction</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Covenant against assignment does not prohibit subletting of the whole or part; covenant construed in tenant&#x27;s favour</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Wilson v Rosenthal [1906]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Alienation \u2014 construction</p></td><td><p>Covenant against subletting the whole does not prohibit subletting of part</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>International Drilling Fluids v Louisville Investments [1986]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Fully qualified covenant \u2014 reasonableness</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Landlord cannot refuse consent on grounds unrelated to the landlord and tenant relationship; sets out basic principles of reasonableness</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Owen v Gadd [1956]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Quiet enjoyment</p></td><td><p>Erection of scaffolding hindering access = breach of landlord&#x27;s covenant for quiet enjoyment</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Kenny v Preen [1963]</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Quiet enjoyment</p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Persistent intimidation of tenant to induce them to leave = breach of covenant for quiet enjoyment</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Moule v Garrett [1872]</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Indemnity (old lease)</p></td><td><p>Former tenant compelled to pay by legal default of another may recover from the defaulting party; quasi-contractual right</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>3. Flashcard Q&amp;A Pairs</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Question</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Answer</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What are the four main leasehold covenants?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Repair; alterations; user; alienation. These are found in most residential and commercial leases.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is the standard of repair under Proudfoot v Hart [1890]?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>The condition a reasonably minded owner would keep the premises in, having regard to: (i) character and type of premises at start of lease; (ii) age of premises; (iii) express wording of the covenant. Does not change with the character of the neighbourhood.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is the distinction between repair and renewal?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Lurcott v Wakely [1911]: &quot;repair is restoration by renewal or replacement of subsidiary parts; renewal is reconstruction of the entirety.&quot; If the whole or substantially the whole needs to be replaced, it is renewal not repair \u2014 outside the tenant&#x27;s covenant.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What are the three types of leasehold covenant and how do they differ?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Absolute: tenant completely prohibited; landlord need not consider any request. Qualified: tenant may request consent; landlord not obliged to grant. Fully qualified: landlord&#x27;s consent not to be unreasonably withheld; reasonableness test applies (International Drilling Fluids [1986]).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is the test of reasonableness for a fully qualified covenant?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>International Drilling Fluids v Louisville [1986]: landlord not entitled to refuse consent on grounds that have nothing to do with the landlord and tenant relationship (e.g. personal dislike of assignee). Must be a genuine L/T reason: ability to pay rent, creditworthiness, bad references.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is the difference between privity of contract and privity of estate?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Privity of contract: original L and T; binding for full lease duration (old leases). Privity of estate: current L and current T; exists only while each holds their respective estate; allows &quot;touch and concern&quot; covenants to be enforced between current parties.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What covenants &quot;touch and concern&quot; the land in an old lease?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Covenants relating to the landlord and tenant relationship; benefit parties in their capacity as L/T; must not be personal. Personal covenants do not touch and concern and do not pass.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is the original tenant&#x27;s position on assignment under an OLD lease?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Privity of contract continues for the full lease duration \u2014 original tenant remains liable for their own AND assignees&#x27; breaches throughout the entire lease term, even after assignment. This can cause hardship.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is the original tenant&#x27;s position on assignment under a NEW lease (LTCA 1995)?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Automatic release on assignment under s 5 LTCA, unless it is an &quot;excluded assignment&quot; (i.e. in breach of alienation covenant under s 11). After release, only liable for breaches during own period of occupation (s 23(1)).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is an AGA and what does it cover?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Authorised guarantee agreement (LTCA 1995 s 16): condition of landlord&#x27;s consent to assignment of a new lease; outgoing tenant guarantees performance of the IMMEDIATE assignee&#x27;s obligations only. On any further assignment, a new AGA is required. Landlord only ever has the current and immediately prior tenant &quot;on the hook.&quot;</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What does LTCA 1995 s 3 provide for new leases?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Automatic transmission of the benefit AND burden of ALL covenants in the lease to the assignee of the lease and to the new reversioner on assignment \u2014 except covenants &quot;expressed to be personal to any person.&quot;</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Is there automatic release of the landlord on assignment under LTCA 1995?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>No \u2014 unlike tenants (s 5), there is no automatic release for landlords. The outgoing landlord must apply to the tenant for release (s 6). If refused, they may apply to court (s 8).</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is the s 17 LTCA tenant default notice requirement?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>The landlord must serve notice of a fixed charge claim on any former tenant who remains liable within 6 months of the charge becoming due. Failure to notify within 6 months = landlord is precluded from claiming. Applies to ALL leases.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What is an overriding lease under s 19 LTCA 1995?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>If a former tenant is required to pay under s 17, they may request an overriding lease \u2014 making them the immediate landlord of the defaulting assignee. Term = remaining term + 3 days; same covenants; allows former tenant to manage, forfeit, or re-let to a more reliable tenant.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Can head landlord enforce covenants against a subtenant?</strong></span></p></td><td><p>No direct relationship exists. S 3(5) LTCA 1995: restrictive covenants in new leases may be enforced against any owner/occupier (including subtenant). Positive covenants cannot be enforced directly against subtenants. Landlord&#x27;s best protection is to require direct covenants from the subtenant as a condition of consent to subletting.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>What happens to a sublease if the headlease is forfeited?</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>The sublease is automatically terminated if the headlease is forfeited \u2014 subject to the subtenant&#x27;s right to apply for relief against forfeiture. This is a strong incentive for the subtenant to comply with the headlease covenants.</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<h3 class=\"notes-h3\"><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>4. Common Exam Pitfalls &amp; Tricky Distinctions</strong></span></h3>\n<div class=\"notes-table-wrap\"><table class=\"notes-table\"><thead><tr><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Pitfall / Distinction</strong></p></th><th class=\"nt-hdr-blue\"><p><strong>Explanation</strong></p></th></tr></thead><tbody>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Always identify old vs new lease first</strong></span></p></td><td><p>The entire enforceability analysis depends on whether the lease was granted before or on/after 1 January 1996. Old leases: privity of contract continues for original parties throughout. New leases: LTCA 1995 governs; automatic transmission under s 3; automatic tenant release under s 5. Never apply old lease rules to a new lease or vice versa.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Excluded assignments: s 5 release does NOT apply</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>An &quot;excluded assignment&quot; (assignment in breach of an alienation covenant, e.g. without landlord&#x27;s consent) does not trigger the s 5 automatic release. The outgoing tenant remains liable. This catches students who assume all assignments lead to automatic release under LTCA 1995.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>AGA only guarantees the IMMEDIATE assignee</strong></span></p></td><td><p>The AGA covers only the obligations of the party to whom the lease is directly assigned. On any subsequent assignment, a new AGA is required. The landlord can only ever look to the current tenant and the one immediately before. Do not say the original tenant is perpetually on the hook via an AGA \u2014 that is the old lease position.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>S 17 LTCA applies to ALL leases \u2014 not just new ones</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Section 17 (and ss 18 and 19) of LTCA 1995 are retrospective provisions that apply to both old and new leases. Failure to serve a s 17 notice within 6 months of the fixed charge becoming due permanently bars the landlord from claiming it from the former tenant. Always check this on facts involving former tenants.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Personal covenants do not pass \u2014 even under new leases</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Under LTCA 1995 s 3(6), covenants &quot;expressed to be personal to any person&quot; are excluded from automatic transmission. This is narrow \u2014 the covenant must be expressly stated to be between two named parties. Do not assume all covenants pass; check for personal wording.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Repair covenant: disrepair at commencement = very onerous</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>A covenant to &quot;keep in repair&quot; includes an obligation to first PUT in repair if the premises are in disrepair at commencement. This can be extremely onerous. The correct drafting tool to limit this is a schedule of condition. Always check whether there is one; if not, the tenant may be responsible for putting the property in good repair from day one.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Repair vs renewal: cost alone is not determinative</strong></span></p></td><td><p>Brew Brothers v Snax: where the cost of works approximates the value of the premises, this can indicate renewal rather than repair. But the question is always one of degree \u2014 whether the whole or substantially the whole is being replaced. Lurcott v Wakely: replacing only the front external wall of a 200-year-old house = repair. Always apply the &quot;subsidiary parts vs entirety&quot; test first.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>Anti-assignment covenant does not restrict subletting</strong></span></p></td><td class=\"nt-cell-blue\"><p>Church v Brown [1808]: a covenant against assignment is construed narrowly in the tenant&#x27;s favour. It does not prevent subletting. Similarly, a covenant against subletting the whole does not prohibit subletting of part (Wilson v Rosenthal [1906]). Always read the precise wording of the alienation covenant and apply this narrow construction.</p></td></tr>\n<tr><td><p><span class=\"nt-txt-blue\"><strong>No direct enforcement against subtenants of positive covenants</strong></span></p></td><td><p>S 3(5) LTCA 1995 only allows restrictive covenants to be enforced against subtenants and occupiers. Positive covenants (repair, pay service charge etc.) cannot be enforced directly by the head landlord against the subtenant. The tenant remains the responsible party and must control the subtenant through the underlease terms.</p></td></tr></tbody></table></div>"}]};
